surveys.narrative:
A targeted survey of Tullibee (Cisco) in Lake Koronis was conducted during mid-late November of 2015 using lake survey gillnets. A targeted survey is generally used for sampling a specific kind of fish or time of year (i.e. spawning season, fall season, etc.) unlike a standard survey which samples a wider range of fish species during the summer months using standard methodology (i.e. standard time of year, set sampling stations, taking water clarity readings and oxygen/temperature profiles, etc.) and gears (i.e. lake survey gillnets, trapnets, and spring electrofishing for bass).

Koronis is a large (2,968 acres), and deep (132 feet maximum) lake located in Stearns County. Tullibee were believed to be initially introduced into Koronis during the 1880's. Green Lake is the only other Spicer Area lake with a self-sustaining Tullibee population. Tullibee spawn in 3-6 feet of water over bottom substrates consisting of large rock during late November to early December when the water temperature reaches 41 degrees Fahrenheit "F" or less. Spawning substrates in both Koronis and Green during recent years have been covered by periphyton/algae except in shallow (<1 foot) windswept shoal areas. Climate changes may be negatively affecting Tullibee natural reproduction/recruitment success in these lakes due to degrading spawning habitat and increasing numbers of warm water fish species (i.e. Rock Bass, Pumpkinseed, Smallmouth Bass, Largemouth Bass, etc.) which prey upon Tullibee eggs, fry or fingerlings.

Adult Tullibee are susceptible to summerkill in Koronis if oxygen levels drop (<2 ppm) in the cooler deeper areas (<74 F) of the lake for an extended time (1-3 weeks) during late July to early August. Young Tullibee can tolerate warmer temperatures than adult Tullibee. A minor summerkill was reported in 2006 for Koronis, but not Green Lake. Low dissolved oxygen (<2 ppm) levels were present in Koronis and Green at depths where preferred adult Tullibee temperatures (<74 F) occurred for a short time period in the 2010 late summer. Although no summerkill of Tullibee was reported for Green Lake, a minor summerkill of adult Tullibee occurred in Koronis during 2010. A major summerkill of Tullibee occurred in Koronis during 2011, but only a minor kill occurred in Green Lake during the 2011 summer. Drought conditions and extremely high air temperatures were the norm for the Spicer Area during July and early August of 2012. There were no apparent summerkills in Green or Koronis during 2012, but adult numbers were so low that summerkill events may not have been recognizable, especially due to the large numbers of pelicans living on Lake Koronis islands. A narrow band (1-3 feet) of marginal temperatures (<74 F) and dissolved oxygen levels (1-3 ppm) was present in depths of 18-25 feet in Koronis during mid-July and early August of 2012. Tullibee summerkill conditions on Koronis were suitable when dissolved oxygen levels were less than 1 ppm at a depth of 20 feet with a water temperature of 76 F on July 24, 2012, but no summerkill events were observed in 2012. Summer temperature and oxygen conditions were more conducive for Tullibee survival during 2013-2015. Green has been the only lake in the Spicer Area open to the public for fall gillnetting of Tullibee during late November or early December each year since the late 1980's. Koronis was closed to public gillnetting during the late 1980's due to low Tullibee populations and high incidence of northern pike mortality during prior open seasons. Green Lake has been closed for Tullibee gillnetting since 2012 due to the low numbers sampled in recent years. Tullibee are an important forage fish for trophy northern pike in Koronis and Green.

Tullibee numbers were low to moderate in a 2014 special assessment (mid-August) using vertical gillnets (20.7 fish/gang, 62 Tullibee total). There were five gillnets set per gang at three different deep water sites from the surface to bottom. Fish ranged in size from 3.1 to 17.5 inches from the seven different mesh sized panels of vertical gillnets. The majority of Tullibee captured were young of year (2014 year class), age 2+ (2012 and 2011) and age 6+ year classes. Unlike vertical gillnets, standard summer lake survey gillnets are comprised of five different mesh sizes per net, 250 feet long and set in water depths with adequate oxygen levels (usually 10-40 feet deep) encompassing 6 feet of depth up from the bottom. Fall gillnet assessments utilize standard summer gillnets, but are set along shallow (< 6 feet) boulder bars during mid/late November when water temperatures are below 41 F.

There were low to moderate numbers of Tullibee (19.7 fish/gillnet) captured in the 2015 fall special assessment. The 2015 fall Tullibee average size was moderate (1.39 pounds and 14.17 inches) for Koronis. Tullibee abundance was lower in 2014 (6.0 fish/gillnet) and 2012 (5.3 fish/gillnet) fall assessments. The fall Tullibee historical average catch rate and average length are 29.6 fish/gillnet and 15.12 inches for Koronis. The fall Tullibee catch rate in nearby Green Lake was low in 2015 (10.3 fish/gillnet, 13.66 inches average length). The 2015 fall Tullibee condition factor (1.271) was above the 50th quartile (1.250) for Koronis. Tullibee growth rates were near or above the Koronis 50th quartiles for ages 2-7. The 2011 year class comprised 46% of the 2015 fall Tullibee catch in Koronis. The 2012 year class comprised 36% of the total 2015 fall catch. A recent increase in Tullibee abundance is encouraging for Koronis. However, the inconsistency of Tullibee natural reproduction and adequate adult Tullibee numbers on the spawning grounds as sampled by the DNR is not a good indication for the long term sustainability of the Tullibee population in Lake Koronis. Hopefully, consecutive cool summers will continue to occur periodically, which may result in a good hatch, recruitment and survival of Tullibee to maintain a long term population in Lake Koronis.

Improving and maintaining good water quality in Koronis is the key for Tullibee numbers to survive and flourish. Public fall Tullibee gillnetting seasons will not be reinstated in the near future on Koronis due to low Tullibee numbers and high incidental catches of other gamefish. Current fish management activities on Koronis include monitoring the fish population on a periodic basis, assisting aquatic plant management and enforcement personnel with invasive species monitoring and education, protecting aquatic vegetation through the permit process, participating in local watershed initiatives, and stocking various fish species as warranted. The Lake Koronis fishery will be sampled in the 2017 summer for all fish species.

A targeted fall night electrofishing survey was conducted for young of year "YOY" (fingerling sized) Walleye on Koronis during October 14, 2021. Previous fall electrofishing surveys were conducted at six stations for a total of 60+ minutes. The 2020 survey (7 stations, 114 minutes) was conducted as part of a larger statewide research study to evaluate fall electrofishing catch effectiveness for different total shocking times. Five stations were sampled for a total of 60 minutes in 2021. The water temperature was 62 F. Moderate waves were noted at one station, but wind/wave action was light at the other stations. Water clarity was good at five of six stations. Submergent vegetation density was light to moderate. We observed moderate numbers of sunfish species, Logperch, Black Crappie and Yellow Perch in the 2021 fall electrofishing survey.

Koronis is a large (2,968 acres), deep (132 feet maximum), and productive lake located primarily in Stearns County. Koronis is a popular fishery for Walleye, Northern Pike, Smallmouth Bass, Largemouth Bass, Black Crappie, Tullibee and Bluegill. Koronis receives moderate recreational use during the summer months. The largest inlet is the North Fork of the Crow River, which enters Koronis along the east shore and outlets near the southeast corner. The greatest volume of nutrient loading is delivered to Koronis via the North Fork of the Crow River. Water levels were below normal during 2021. An invasive algal species, starry stonewort, was found primarily in the east and outlet bays of Koronis in 2015 and near the south access of Rice Lake in 2016. Current efforts to chemically eradicate starry stonewort have been unsuccessful in Koronis. Aquatic vegetation densities are variable yearly in the lake.

Rice Lake is upstream and connects to Lake Koronis via the North Fork of the Crow River. In the past, Walleye from both Rice and Koronis have spawned in the North Fork of the Crow River upstream of Rice Lake. A Walleye egg take station was operated just upstream of Rice Lake in the Crow River from the 1970's to 1992. However, this Walleye spawning run now appears to be considerably reduced. This is based on anecdotal observations of lower opening Walleye fishing activity near the Koronis inlet bay/narrows area especially since the 2000's and recent (2018-2019) ice out hoop netting in the river near the old egg take station. Walleye fishing activity often was higher during late ice off years at the Koronis inlet bay area due to fish returning from upriver spawning around opening weekend. Walleye also spawn adjacent to the east shores of the three islands in Koronis and the east point of Rice. Since 2001, both Rice and Koronis have been periodic "Spicer Strain" Walleye egg take sites for the statewide Walleye propagation program. Other recent Spicer Strain egg take lakes include Diamond and Elizabeth. Historic spawning sites for Walleye in both Koronis and Rice have been degraded in recent years with increased sedimentation, algal and periphyton growth.

Walleye natural reproduction in Koronis has been frequent and often adequate to sustain Walleye numbers based on previous fall and summer surveys and markings. However, natural reproduction contribution has been more variable in recent years due in part to degraded spawning habitat and unfavorable spring conditions. Walleye fry (0.5-2.0 million/year) were stocked during 1996 and 2001-2019 as a 10% return of Walleye eggs taken for the DNR statewide Walleye hatching program. Spicer strain Walleye fry have been primarily stocked since 2004. No Walleye eggs were taken and no fry were stocked in 2020. In 2021, 968,348 Spicer strain Walleye were stocked into Koronis. Walleye fingerlings were recently stocked in 2004 (2,409 pounds, 48,180 fish), combination of ages (2,355 pounds, 45,685 fish) were stocked in 2006, and a combination of yearlings/fingerlings (867 pounds, 4,887 fish) were stocked in the 2010.

YOY Walleye numbers were abundant (65.00 YOY/hour, 7.23 inches) in 2021 fall electrofishing survey. No Yearling Walleye were observed in 2021. Moderate YOY Walleye numbers (23.16 YOY/hour, 7.62 inches) were captured in 2020 fall electrofishing survey. We also observed moderate numbers of yearling (9.47 fish/hour) and age 2+ (23.16 fish/hour) Walleye in the 2020 survey. Low YOY Walleye numbers were captured in 2019 (1.85 YOY/hour). Abundant yearling Walleye were captured in 2019 (13.85 fish/hour, 9.76 inches). Moderate YOY and yearling Walleye numbers were captured in 2018 (20.57 YOY/hour, 7.20 inches; 8.57 yearlings/hour, 9.71 inches). Abundant YOY Walleye numbers were captured in 2017 (65.60 YOY/hour, 6.03 inches). OTC marked fish accounted for 33% of the YOY Walleye catch in the 2017 fall. Low numbers of yearling Walleye were captured in 2017 (4.80 fish/hour, 9.90 inches). Low YOY Walleye numbers were captured in 2016 (14.18 YOY/hour, 6.51 inches). OTC marked fish accounted for 40% of the 2016 Fall YOY Walleye catch. Yearling and two year old Walleye numbers were abundant (17.45 fish/hour) in 2016. Low YOY Walleye numbers (3.60 YOY/hour, 5.97 inches) were captured in 2015. There were no OTC marked YOY walleye captured in the 2015 fall electrofishing survey. Yearling Walleye numbers were abundant (22.80 fish/hour, 9.45 inches) in 2015. Abundant numbers of YOY Walleye were captured in 2014 (208.09 YOY/hour, 6.39 inches average length) and 2013 (71.25 YOY/hour, 5.79 inches average length). OTC marked fish accounted for 82% of the 2014 Walleye fingerlings captured in the fall electrofishing survey. Approximately 45% of the 2013 fall electrofishing YOY catch were OTC marked (fry stocked). Moderate YOY Walleye numbers (32.83 YOY/hour, 6.97 inches) were captured in the 2012 fall electrofishing survey. Approximately 92% of the 2012 year class fish captured in the 2012 fall electrofishing survey were OTC marked (fry stocked). Abundant numbers of YOY Walleye (205.50 YOY/hour, 6.50 inches) were captured in the 2011 fall electrofishing survey. Approximately 80% (164.40 YOY/hour) were OTC marked fish in the 2011 fall electrofishing survey. The Koronis YOY Walleye historical average catch rate and average length are 42.19 YOY/hour and 6.67 inches.

Walleye abundance (17.00 fish/gillnet) was above the historical average catch rate (10.93 fish/gillnet) for Koronis in the most recent 2019 standard summer survey. The 2019 Walleye average size was moderate (1.28 pounds and 14.69 inches) from gillnets. The Walleye historical average length is 14.01 inches from gillnets. The 2019 catch rate of quality size (15.00 inches and larger) Walleye (7.60 fish/gillnet) was higher than the historical average (4.49 fish/gillnet) for Koronis. The 2016 and 2017 year classes (fry stocked and natural reproduction) comprised 36% and 19% respectively of the 2019 Walleye gillnet and trapnet catch. Walleye fry were marked with Oxytetracycline "OTC" in 2009 and 2011-2017 to determine the contribution of natural reproduction versus stocking. OTC marked fish (fry stocked) comprised 38%, 25%, 33%, 50%, 100% and 100% respectively of the 2016, 2015, 2014, 2013, 2012 and 2011 year classes in the 2019 summer survey catch.

Current fish management activities on Koronis include protecting the important aquatic vegetation such as bulrush through the permit process, participating in local watershed projects, assisting aquatic plant management and enforcement personnel with invasive species monitoring and education, stocking various species as needed, and stocking Walleye fingerlings after two consecutive years of poor natural reproduction as documented by fall night electrofishing surveys. The Koronis fishery will be surveyed again for YOY Walleye in the 2022 fall by electrofishing and 2022 for all fish species by standard survey gears.

THE 1991 NOP INDEX (2.13 PER GN) WAS LOWER THAN THE MAJORITY OF CLASS 22 LAKES, BUT WAS SIMILAR TO THE HISTORICAL MEAN (1.74 PER GN) AND MEDIAN (1.63 PER GN) FOR LAKE KORONIS (9 SURVEY'S). THE MAJORITY OF NORTHERNS SAMPLED WERE FROM THE 1988 AND 1989 YEAR-CLASS (IN BOTH THE 1990 AND 1991 SURVEY'S) AND SHOWED AVERAGE GROWTH RATES. THE 1990 YEAR-CLASS DID NOT SHOW ANY INDICATIONS OF BEING A STRONG ONE. BASED ON THE LAST 5 CONSECUTIVE SURVEY'S (1987-1991), THE NOP CATCH INDICES WERE RELATIVELY HIGHER IN 1990 AND 1991 THAN IN 1987-1989. THE 1991 BLG CATCH INDEX (3.13 PER TN) WAS LOWER THAN THE MAJORITY OF CLASS 22 LAKES. THE 1991 INDEX (3.13 PER TN) IS ALSO THE CURRENT MEDIAN FOR THE 9 SURVEY'S DONE ON LAKE KORONIS. THE GILLNET SAMPLING IN LAKE KORONIS APPEARS TO SAMPLE THE RELATIVE DENSITY OF THE 1990 GILLNET INDICES (4.33, 1.07 LBS.) WAS THE HIGHEST RECORDED FOR BLG IN KORONIS WHICH COINCIDED WITH GOOD-EXCELLENT BLG FISHING THAT YEAR. THE 1991 INDICES (2.75 PER GN, 0.70 LBS.) COINCIDED WITH A RELATIVE DECLINE IN FISHING SUCCESS FOR BLG. THE 1988 YEAR-CLASS MOST LIKELY PROVIDED THE BULK OF THE HARVEST IN 1990 (PARTICULARLY IN THE LATE SUMMER/FALL). THE 1990 AND 1991 AGE-CLASS DISTRIBUTIONS SUGGESTED A HEAVY MORTALITY FOR THE 1988 AGE-CLASS (66 INDIVUALS AGE 2+ INDIVIDUALS SAMPLED IN 1990, 11 AGE 3+ INDIVIDUAL SAMPLED IN 1991). THE 1990 YEAR-CLASS DID NOT GIVE ANY INDICATION OF BEING A STRONG ONE. THE ABOVE AVERAGE GROWTH RATES SEEN IN KORONIS ALLOWS A PROPORTION OF THE AGE 2+ BLGS TO REACH HARVESTABLE SIZE (>6.0 3RD GROWING SEASON. THE 1991 SMB CATCH INDEX (1.63 PER GN) WAS HIGHER THAN THE MAJORITY OF OTHER CLASS 22 LAKES AND WAS THE HIGHEST EVER RECORDED ON LAKE KORONIS (SMB FISHING HAS ALSO REPORTEDLY BEEN EXCELLENT RECENTLY). GROWTH RATES ARE GOOD AS IT TAKES JUST 3 GROWING SEASONS TO REACH AN AVERAGE OF 12.5 INCHES. SMB SPRING ELECTROFISHING SAMPLING HAS BEEN UNSUCCESSFUL THUS FAR (1990 AND 1991). THE LMB 1991 SPRING ELECTROFISHING SAMPLE YIELDED A SIMILAR SIZE DISTRIBUTION AS THE 1990 SAMPLE (1991, PSD=17, RSD-P=3:1990, PSD=16,RSD-P=6). DENSITY INDICES FOR BOTH YEARS WERE SIMILAR TO THE MAJORITY OF OTHER SPICER AREA LAKES (1991, 26.40 PER HOUR: 1990, 36.68 PER HOUR). THERE WERE NO AGE 1+ (1990 YEAR-CLASS) LMB SAMPLED IN THE 1991 SURVEY, WHEREAS, THERE WERE 24 AGE 1+ (1989 YEAR-CLASS) LMB SAMPLED IN THE 1990 SURVEY. THE 1991 BLC TRAPNET CATCH INDEX (0.33 PER SET) WAS LOWER THAN THE MAJORITY OF OTHER CLASS 22 LAKES (THE 1991 GILLNET CATCH INDEX WAS 0.63 PER SET AND WAS THE HIGHEST EVER RECORDED FOR LAKE KORONIS). THE MAJORITY OF SAMPLED BLC WERE FROM THE 1989 YEAR- CLASS AND SHOULD BE FOR THE 1992 FISHING SEASON WITH THEIR ABOVE AVERAGE GROWTH RATES. THE 1991 YEP CATCH INDEX (48.00 PER GN) WAS HIGHER THAN THE MAJORITY OF OTHER CLASS 22 LAKES, HOWEVER, MUCH HIGHER CATCH INDICES ARE NOT UNCOMMON FOR THIS LAKE (1982- 293.70, 1977- 196.80, 1969 - 79.70). THE 1991 INDEX, HOWEVER, WAS THE HIGHEST IN THE LAST 5 SURVEY'S (1987-1991) WHICH SHOW A DEFINITE INCREASE IN THE 1990, 1991 SAMPLES RELATIVE TO THE 1987-1989 SAMPLES. GROWTH RATES WERE SLIGHTLY LOWER IN THE 1991 SURVEY RELATIVE TO THE 1990 SURVEY. THE 1989 YEAR-CLASS APPEARS DOMINANT FOR YEP AND COULD PROVIDE 1992 IN HIGH NUMBERS. THE 1991 WAE CATCH INDEX (4.25 PER GN) WAS THE LOWEST EVER RECORDED FOR LAKE KORONIS, BUT WAS SIMILAR TO THE MAJORITY OF OTHER CLASS 22 LAKES (LBS. PER GN, 3.93, WAS LOWER THAN THE MAJORITY OF CLASS 22 LAKES). CONVERSELY, THE WAE TRAPNET CATCH INDEX (3.93) WAS THE HIGHEST EVER RECORDED FOR LAKE KORONIS. THE AVERAGE SIZE OF SAMPLED WAE WAS SMALL (GN-0.92 LBS., TN - 0.91 LBS.), HOWEVER, THIS IS NOT UNUSUAL FOR LAKE KORONIS (SEE HISTORICAL CATCH SUMMARY). GROWTH RATES WERE CONSIDERED BELOW AVERAGE WHICH IS TYPICAL FOR LAKE KORONIS, HOWEVER, THE GROWTH RATES APPEARED SLIGHTLY HIGHER THAN THE 1990 GROWTH RATES (AGES 4 AND 5 IN 1991, 14.7 INCHES AND 16.6 INCHES: AGES 4 AND 5 IN 1990 13.2 AND 15.6 INCHES). OVERALL, THE WAE CATCH INDICES APPEAR DOWN WITH A SLIGHT INCREASE IN GROWTH RATES. THE INCREASE IN THE YEP AND SMB CATCH INDICES (GROWTH RATES FOR YEP AND SMB ALSO DECLINED SLIGHTLY) MAY HAVE BEEN INFLUENCED BY THE APPARENT MODERATE DECREASE OF WAE. THE AGE-CLASS DISTRIBUTION FROM THE 1990 AND 1991 SURVEY SHOW A RELATIVELY STRONG 1989 YEAR-CLASS (NATURALLY REPRODUCED AND A WEAK 1990 YEAR-CLASS (FINGERLINGS STOCKED). CATCH INDICES OF CERTAIN NON-GAMEFISH SPECIES (PARTICULARLY BLB, CAP, AND WTS) WERE ALL HIGHER THAN THE MAJORITY OF OTHER CLASS 22 LAKES. MOST APPARENT IS THE SUBSTANTIAL INCREASE IN BLB GILLNET CATCH INDICES THE PAST 5 SURVEY'S COMPARED TO THE 1982 AND EARLIER SURVEY'S. THE 1991 BLB GILLNET CATCH INDEX WAS 91.25 PER SET WHICH WAS THE HIGHEST EVER RECORDED FOR LAKE KORONIS (1990 INDEX: 76.33 PER SET, SEE HISTORICAL CATCH SUMMARY). WTS AND CAP DO NOT SHOW THE SAME DRAMATIC INCREASE IN CATCH INDICES, HOWEVER, THE 1991 TRAPNET CATCH INDEX FOR CAP WAS THE HIGHEST EVER RECORDED FOR LAKE KORONIS (3.87 PER SET, BUT ONLY 5.30 LBS. PER SET). THERE WAS AN UNUSUALLY HIGH NUMBER OF 7-11 INCH CAP IN THE 1991 SAMPLE (CAP LESS THAN 12 INCHES HAVE BEEN VERY RARE IN PAST LAKE SURVEY'S). THE SUMMER TESTNETTING FOR CISCO HAS HAD RELATIVELY POOR SUCCESS DURING THE 1987-1991 SURVEY'S RELATIVE TO THE EARLIER SURVEY'S; HOWEVER, FALL TESTNETTING IN 1991 SHOWED THERE IS A SPAWNING CISCO POPULATION DOMINATED BY VERY LARGE INDIVIDUALS.

A population assessment of Lake Koronis was conducted in late July of 2010. Koronis is a large, deep, and productive lake located primarily in Stearns County. Koronis is a popular fishery for walleye, northern pike, smallmouth bass, tullibee and bluegill. The lake is highly developed with approximately 498 homes and cabins, and seven resorts/bible camp/campgrounds. In addition, the city of Paynesville is within two miles of the lake. The immediate watershed is composed primarily of agricultural row crops, hardwood areas, and residential development. Nutrient runoff enters Koronis via 45 inlets/tiles (mostly small inlets) from agricultural, city storm sewer, and lake residential sources. The largest inlet and greatest nutrient contributor is the North Fork of the Crow River, which enters Koronis along the east shore and outlets near the southeast corner. The greatest volume of nutrient loading is delivered to Koronis via the North Fork of the Crow River. Nutrient levels (total phosphorus=0.030 ppm, chlorophyll a=24.0 ppb) were moderate in June of 2007 for Koronis. Aquatic vegetation densities are variable yearly in the lake. Water clarity was fair (4.5 feet) during the 2010 summer in Koronis. Water temperatures were stratified by July of 2010. Low (<1.0 ppm) or no oxygen was present in depths below 30 feet during the late 2010 summer. A minor summerkill of large sized tullibee (cisco) was noted during late July - early August of 2010. Partial summerkills of tullibee and white suckers are common in Koronis during hot summers. Koronis is a periodic walleye egg take site for the statewide walleye propagation program. Koronis is managed primarily for walleye and northern pike, in addition to secondary species such as bluegill, yellow perch, tullibee, bass, and black crappie.

Black crappie numbers were abundant in 2010 (7.50 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal ranges for Koronis and similar lakes. The Koronis black crappie historical average catch rate is 1.11 fish/gillnet. The 2010 black crappie average size was moderate (0.35 pounds and 7.51 inches) from gillnets. The black crappie historical average length is 8.16 inches from gillnets. The 2010 catch rate of preferred size (10.00 inches) and larger black crappie was moderate (2.67 fish/gillnet). Black crappie growth rates were within the Spicer Area normal ranges for ages 1-5. The 2009 and 2005 year classes comprised 57% and 28% respectively of the 2010 black crappie gillnet and trapnet catch in Koronis.

Bluegill numbers were low to moderate in 2010 (5.13 fish/trapnet) compared to the normal ranges for Koronis and similar lakes. The Koronis bluegill historical average catch rate is 8.84 fish/trapnet. The 2010 bluegill average size was moderate (0.22 pounds and 6.03 inches) from the trapnets. The bluegill historical average length is 5.03 inches from trapnets. The 2010 catch rate of quality size (6.00 inches) and larger bluegill was low (3.27 fish/trapnet).

Northern pike numbers were moderate to high in 2010 (3.33 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal ranges for Koronis, but below the normal range for similar lakes. The Koronis northern pike historical average catch rate is 2.73 fish/gillnet. The 2010 northern pike average size was moderate (4.53 pounds and 26.41 inches) from gillnets. The northern pike historical average length is 23.62 inches from gillnets. The 2010 catch rate of preferred size (28.00 inches) and larger northern pike was low to moderate (1.00 fish/gillnet). Northern pike growth rates in Koronis were generally above the Spicer Area normal ranges for ages 1-6. The 2004 and 2006-2008 year classes each comprised about 20% of the 2010 northern pike gillnet and trapnet catch. The largest northern pike captured was 33.27 inches in the 2010 assessment.

Smallmouth bass numbers were abundant in 2010 (2.33 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal ranges for Koronis and similar lakes. The smallmouth bass historical average catch rate is 0.79 fish/gillnet from Koronis. The 2010 smallmouth bass average size was large (1.82 pounds and 14.11 inches) from gillnets. The smallmouth bass historical average length is 12.88 inches from gillnets. The 2010 catch rate of preferred size (14.00 inches) and larger smallmouth bass was high (1.50 fish/gillnet) compared to the historical average (0.48 fish/gillnet). The largest smallmouth bass captured was 19.69 inches in 2010.

Largemouth bass are not sampled efficiently with summer gillnets and trapnets (due to net avoidance) compared to the preferred gear of spring electrofishing. We did not conduct a 2010 spring electrofishing in Koronis due to time constraints with other fisheries activities. Largemouth bass numbers were not abundant in the 2010 gillnets (0.17 fish/gillnet). However, local anglers have reported largemouth bass numbers abundant in their catch in recent years.

Tullibee "cisco" numbers were moderately abundant in 2010 (2.50 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal ranges for Koronis and similar lakes. The tullibee historical summer average catch rate is 1.27 fish/gillnet for Koronis. The 2010 tullibee summer average size was moderate (1.00 pounds and 12.19 inches) from gillnets. The tullibee summer historical average length is 12.30 inches from gillnets. Tullibee abundance was moderate (23.8 fish/gillnet, 15.28 inches average length) in the 2010 fall gillnet special assessment. It appears that the 2010 tullibee summerkill had a minimal effect on population numbers in Koronis.

There were moderate numbers of tullibee (23.8 fish/gillnet) captured in the 2010 fall special assessment. The 2010 tullibee average size was large (1.49 pounds and 15.29 inches), but similar to the historical average (15.15 inches). The fall tullibee historical average catch rate is 33.2 fish/gillnet . The tullibee condition factor in the 2010 fall (1.268) was moderate for Koronis. Tullibee growth rates were below the Koronis normal ranges for ages 1-7. The 2003, 2002 and 2001 year classes comprised 18%, 30% and 32% respectively of the 2010 fall tullibee catch. It appears that smaller sized tullibee (2007 year class) were sampled more frequently in the 2010 summer gillnet sets than in the fall spawning station gillnet sets of Koronis. The 2007 year class tullibee may not have been sexually mature for spawning in 2010, thus these fish were not adequately sampled in the fall. Hopefully, cool summers will occur during the next several years, which may result in a good hatch and survival of tullibee in Koronis if adequate brood stock numbers are still present. Tullibee are an important forage species for both large northern pike and walleye.

Yellow perch numbers were moderately abundant in 2010 (56.50 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal ranges for Koronis and similar lakes. The yellow perch historical average catch rate is 61.80 fish/gillnet for Koronis. The 2010 yellow perch average size was moderate (0.16 pounds and 7.16 inches) from gillnets. The yellow perch historical average length is 7.03 inches from gillnets. The 2010 catch rate of quality size (8.00 inches) and larger yellow perch was low (4.50 fish/gillnet).

Walleye numbers were abundant in 2010 (16.33 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal ranges for Koronis and similar lakes. The walleye historical average catch rate is 9.39 fish/gillnet for Koronis. The 2010 walleye average size was moderate (1.38 pounds and 14.97 inches) from gillnets. The walleye historical average length is 13.96 inches from gillnets. The 2010 catch rate of quality size (15.00 inches) and larger walleye (7.00 fish/gillnet) was higher than the historical average (3.53 fish/gillnet) for Koronis. Walleye growth rates were generally near or below the Spicer Area normal ranges for ages 1-4, but within or above the normal ranges for ages 5-8. The 2007 and 2008 year classes (fry stocked and natural reproduction) comprised 36% and 24% of the 2010 walleye gillnet and trapnet catch. The 2006 year class (fingerling & fry stocked, natural reproduction) comprised 18% of the 2010 walleye gillnet and trapnet catch.

Walleye natural reproduction in Koronis was generally both frequent and adequate to sustain walleye numbers based on previous fall and summer surveys from 1993-2002. In recent years, walleye natural reproduction has been poor except for 2007-08. Walleye young of year "YOY" numbers were low (6.43 YOY/hour, 7.27 inches average length) in 2010 fall electrofishing survey. The fall electrofishing YOY walleye historical average catch rate is 27.63 YOY/hour for Koronis. Current fish management activities on Koronis include protecting the important aquatic vegetation such as bulrush through the permit process, participating in local watershed projects, assisting aquatic plant management and enforcement personnel in educating boaters and monitoring access sites for potential invasive species introductions, stocking various species as needed, and stocking walleye fingerlings after two consecutive years of poor natural reproduction as documented by fall night electrofishing surveys. The Koronis fishery will be surveyed again for YOY walleye in the 2011 fall.

A targeted survey of Tullibee "Cisco" in Lake Koronis was conducted during mid-late November of 2017 using lake survey gillnets. A targeted survey is generally used for sampling a specific kind of fish or time of year (i.e. spawning season, fall season, etc.) unlike a standard survey which samples a wider range of fish species during the summer months using standard methodology (i.e. standard time of year, set sampling stations, taking water clarity readings and oxygen/temperature profiles, etc.) and gears (i.e. lake survey gillnets, trapnets, and spring electrofishing for Largemouth Bass).

Koronis is a large (2,968 acres), and deep (132 feet maximum) lake located in Stearns County. Tullibee were believed to be initially introduced into Koronis during the 1880's. Green Lake is the only other Spicer Area lake with a self-sustaining Tullibee population. Tullibee spawn in 3-6 feet of water over bottom substrates consisting of large rock during late November to early December when the water temperature reaches 41 degrees Fahrenheit "F" or less. Spawning substrates in both Koronis and Green during recent years have been covered by periphyton/algae except in shallow (<1 foot) windswept shoal areas. Climate changes may be negatively affecting Tullibee natural reproduction/recruitment success in these lakes due to degrading spawning habitat and increasing numbers of warm water fish species (i.e. Rock Bass, Pumpkinseed, Smallmouth Bass, Largemouth Bass, etc.) which prey upon Tullibee eggs, fry or fingerlings.

Adult Tullibee are susceptible to summerkill in Koronis if oxygen levels drop (<2 ppm) in the cooler deeper areas (<74 F) of the lake for an extended time (1-3 weeks) during late July to early August. Young Tullibee can tolerate warmer temperatures than adult Tullibee. A minor summerkill was reported in 2006 for Koronis, but not Green Lake. Low dissolved oxygen (<2 ppm) levels were present in Koronis and Green at depths where preferred adult Tullibee temperatures (<74 F) occurred for a short time period in the 2010 late summer. Although no summerkill of Tullibee was reported for Green Lake, a minor summerkill of adult Tullibee occurred in Koronis during 2010. A major summerkill of Tullibee occurred in Koronis during 2011, but only a minor kill occurred in Green Lake during the 2011 summer. Drought conditions and extremely high air temperatures were the norm for the Spicer Area during July and early August of 2012. There were no apparent summerkills in Green or Koronis during 2012, but adult numbers were so low that summerkill events may not have been recognizable, especially due to the large numbers of pelicans living on Lake Koronis islands. Summer temperature and oxygen conditions were more conducive for Tullibee survival during 2013-2017. An adequate band of water temperatures (<74 F) and dissolved oxygen levels (2-8 ppm) was present at depths of 15-24 feet in Koronis during mid-July of 2017. Green has been the only lake in the Spicer Area open to the public for fall gillnetting of Tullibee during late November or early December each year since the late 1980's. Koronis was closed to public gillnetting during the late 1980's due to low Tullibee populations and high incidence of northern pike mortality during prior open seasons. Green Lake has been closed for Tullibee gillnetting since 2012 due to the low numbers sampled in recent years. Tullibee are an important forage fish for trophy northern pike in Koronis and Green.

Tullibee numbers were not present in the 2017 summer standard survey catch. The Tullibee historical summer average catch rate is 1.1 fish/gillnet for Koronis. The Tullibee summer historical average length is 11.91 inches from gillnets.

Tullibee abundance was low (10.3 fish/gillnet) in the 2017 fall gillnet targeted survey. The 2017 fall Tullibee average size was moderate (1.53 pounds and 14.39 inches). Tullibee abundance was moderate in the 2010 (23.8 fish/gillnet, 15.28 inches) and 2015 (19.7 fish/gillnet, 14.17 inches) fall gillnet targeted surveys, but low in 2012 (5.33 fish/gillnet) and 2014 (6.00 fish/gillnet). The Tullibee fall historical average catch rate and average length are 30.1 fish/gillnet and 15.20 inches for Koronis. The Tullibee fall catch rate in nearby Green Lake was low in 2017 (0.5 fish/gillnet, 11.25 inches) and 2015 (10.3 fish/gillnet, 13.66 inches average length). Tullibee growth rates were generally within the Spicer Area normal ranges. The 2012 and 2014 year classes comprised 34% and 31% respectively of the 2017 Tullibee fall catch in Koronis. The 2013 and 2011 year classes each comprised about 16% of the 2017 Tullibee fall catch. Hopefully, consecutive cool summers will continue to occur periodically, which may result in a good hatch, recruitment and survival of Tullibee to maintain a long term population in Lake Koronis.

Improving and maintaining good water quality in Koronis is the key for Tullibee numbers to survive and flourish. Public fall Tullibee gillnetting seasons will not be reinstated in the near future on Koronis due to low Tullibee numbers and high incidental catches of other gamefish. Current fish management activities on Koronis include monitoring the fish population on a periodic basis, assisting aquatic plant management and enforcement personnel with invasive species monitoring and education, protecting aquatic vegetation through the permit process, participating in local watershed initiatives, and stocking various fish species as warranted. The Lake Koronis fishery will be sampled in the 2019 summer for all fish species.

A targeted fall night electrofishing survey was conducted for young of year "YOY" (fingerling sized) Walleye on Koronis during October 15, 2020. Previous fall electrofishing surveys were conducted at six stations for a total of 60+ minutes. The 2020 survey was conducted as part of a larger statewide research study to evaluate fall electrofishing catch effectiveness for different total shocking times. Seven stations were sampled for a total of 114 minutes in 2020. The water temperature was 54 F. Submergent vegetation density was moderate. We observed moderate numbers of Bluegill, Black Crappie, Rock Bass, Brook Silverside, Shiners and Yellow Perch in the 2020 fall electrofishing survey.

Koronis is a large (2,968 acres), deep (132 feet maximum), and productive lake located primarily in Stearns County. Koronis is a popular fishery for Walleye, Northern Pike, Smallmouth Bass, Largemouth Bass, Black Crappie, Tullibee and Bluegill. Koronis receives moderate recreational use during the summer months. The largest inlet is the North Fork of the Crow River, which enters Koronis along the east shore and outlets near the southeast corner. The greatest volume of nutrient loading is delivered to Koronis via the North Fork of the Crow River. Water levels were below normal during 2020. An invasive algal species, starry stonewort, was found primarily in the east and outlet bays of Koronis in 2015 and near the south access of Rice Lake in 2016. Current efforts to chemically eradicate starry stonewort have been unsuccessful in Koronis. Aquatic vegetation densities are variable yearly in the lake.

Rice Lake is upstream and connects to Lake Koronis via the North Fork of the Crow River. In the past, Walleye from both Rice and Koronis have spawned in the North Fork of the Crow River upstream of Rice Lake. A Walleye egg take station was operated just upstream of Rice Lake in the Crow River from the 1970's to 1992. However, this Walleye spawning run now appears to be considerably reduced. This is based on anecdotal observations of lower opening Walleye fishing activity near the Koronis inlet bay/narrows area especially since the 2000's and recent (2018-2019) ice out hoop netting in the river near the old egg take station. Walleye fishing activity often was higher during late ice off years at the Koronis inlet bay area due to gfish returning from upriver spawning around opening weekend. Walleye also spawn adjacent to the east shores of the three islands in Koronis and the east point of Rice. Since 2001, both Rice and Koronis have been periodic "Spicer Strain" Walleye egg take sites for the statewide Walleye propagation program. Other recent Spicer Strain egg take lakes include Diamond and Elizabeth. Historic spawning sites for Walleye in both Koronis and Rice have been degraded in recent years with increased sedimentation, algal and periphyton growth.

Walleye natural reproduction in Koronis has been frequent and often adequate to sustain Walleye numbers based on previous fall and summer surveys and markings. However, natural reproduction contribution has been more variable in recent years due in part to degraded spawning habitat and unfavorable spring conditions. Walleye fry (0.5-2.0 million/year) were stocked during 1996 and 2001-2019 as a 10% return of Walleye eggs taken for the DNR statewide Walleye hatching program. No Walleye eggs were taken and no fry were stocked in 2020. Walleye fingerlings were recently stocked in 2004 (2,409 pounds, 48,180 fish), combination of ages (2,355 pounds, 45,685 fish) were stocked in 2006, and a combination of yearlings/fingerlings (867 pounds, 4,887 fish) were stocked in the 2010.

Abundant YOY Walleye numbers were captured in 2017 (65.60 YOY/hour, 6.03 inches). OTC marked fish accounted for 33% of the YOY Walleye catch in the 2017 fall. Low numbers of yearling Walleye were captured in 2017 (4.80 fish/hour, 9.90 inches). Low YOY Walleye numbers were captured in 2016 (14.18 YOY/hour, 6.51 inches). OTC marked fish accounted for 40% of the 2016 Fall YOY Walleye catch. Yearling and two year old Walleye numbers were abundant (17.45 fish/hour) in 2016. Abundant numbers of YOY Walleye were captured in 2014 (208.09 YOY/hour, 6.39 inches average length) and 2013 (71.25 YOY/hour, 5.79 inches average length). OTC marked fish accounted for 82% of the 2014 Walleye fingerlings captured in the fall electrofishing survey. Approximately 45% of the 2013 fall electrofishing YOY catch were OTC marked (fry stocked). Moderate YOY Walleye numbers (32.83 YOY/hour, 6.97 inches) were captured in the 2012 fall electrofishing survey. Approximately 92% of the 2012 year class fish captured in the 2012 fall electrofishing survey were OTC marked (fry stocked). Abundant numbers of YOY Walleye (205.50 YOY/hour, 6.50 inches) were captured in the 2011 fall electrofishing survey. Approximately 80% (164.40 YOY/hour) were OTC marked fish in the 2011 fall electrofishing survey.

Walleye abundance in 2019 gillnets (17.00 fish/gillnet) was above the historical average catch rate (10.93 fish/gillnet) for Koronis. The 2019 Walleye average weight and length were 1.28 pounds and 14.69 inches respectively from gillnets. The Walleye historical average length is 14.01 inches from gillnets. The 2019 catch rate of quality size (15.00 inches and larger) Walleye (7.60 fish/gillnet) was higher than the historical average (4.49 fish/gillnet) for Koronis. The 2016 and 2017 year classes (fry stocked and natural reproduction) comprised 36% and 19% respectively of the 2019 Walleye gillnet and trapnet catch. OTC marked fish (fry stocked) comprised 38%, 25%, 33%, 50%, 100% and 100% respectively of the 2016, 2015, 2014, 2013, 2012 and 2011 year classes in the 2019 summer survey catch.

Koronis is a large (3,014 acres) nutrient rich lake with 13.6 miles of shoreline. It hasa maximum depth of 132 feet. There are a chain of three large islands located along thenorthwest portion of the lake. The shoalwater substrates are mostly gravel, sand, rubble, andboulder. There are several distinct bays (Outlet, Assembly Grounds, Northwest, East, andWest) within the lake. Submergent vegetation densities often vary annually, but are generallygreatest in the east, west, and northwest bay areas. Emergent vegetation (hardstem bulrush)is located near Hendrickson Creek inlet and on the west side of Second Island. The North Forkof the Crow River flows into the east side of Koronis with the outlet located on thesoutheast side. The North Fork of the Crow River watershed comprises about 198,400 acres.There are also about ten small spring/marsh originated inlets that flow into Koronis.Nutrient (phosphorous, nitrogen) loading from the Crow River watershed is a continualproblem. Total phosphorous was 0.131 ppm at the North Fork of Crow River inlet, 0.205 ppm at75 feet (hypolimnion) of the water quality station, and 0.038 ppm at the surface of the waterquality station on 6-18-91. Algae blooms are common during the summer. The secchi discreading was 4.2 feet on 7-19-94. Local residents reported that the water clarity in 1994 wasbetter than previous years in addition to less frequent summer algae blooms. Koronis ishighly developed with about 491 homes/cabins, 5 resorts, several parks, and the AssemblyGrounds Bible Camp. The lake has been primarily managed for northern pike and walleye.Intensive walleye fingerling stocking occurred about every other year (3,000 - 6,000 lbs peryear) during the 1980's. Recently, Koronis has been stocked every other year as needed (1,200lbs of fingerlings per stocking). There are two northern pike spawning areas (Spaeth andHendrickson NPSA) that are operated on Koronis. Previously, Koronis was opened for fall cisco"tullibee" gillnetting, but has been closed since the early 1980's due to low numbersresulting from summerkills (1983, 1987, 1988). Currently, the cisco population appears tohave rebounded, but there are no plans to re-open the fall gillnetting season. Koronis is apopular fishing lake for walleye, northern pike, yellow perch, and smallmouth bass. Walleye abundance in 1994 (11.6 fish/gillnet) was above the normal range (4.0 - 9.6fish/gillnet) for similar lakes and above the historical average (7.9 fish/gillnet). The 1994average size (1.0 lbs from gillnets) was the same as the historical average. The largest fishcaptured was 28.3 inches. Walleye 1994 catch rates of quality size (15-20 inches) andpreferred size (20-25 inches) fish were the highest recorded values (5.6 and 1.1 fish/netrespectively) with historical averages of 2.0 and 0.5 fish/net respectively. Growth ratesappear average. There appears to be several good year classes present, especially the 1992year class. In 1993, natural reproduction was documented by fall electrofishing (37.8 youngof year/hour, average length=6.0 inches). The walleye yearling electrofishing catch rate wasalso 37.8 fish/hour (average length=10.0 inches), but these fish could be from either or botha 1992 stocking and natural reproduction. In the fall of 1993, 17,941 fingerlings (14.5fish/lb.) were fin clipped (left pelvic fin) and stocked into Koronis. We caught 2 finclipped fingerlings out of 72 fish from the 1993 year class during a 1994 springelectrofishing survey (2.8% of total). Fin clipped walleyes accounted for 19.4% of the 1993year class fish caught in the 1994 summer survey. In the 1994 fall electrofishing survey, finclipped yearlings accounted for 7.8% of the total 1993 year class captured. The 1994 fallelectrofishing catch rates were 10.5 young of year/hour (average size=6.5 inches) and 38.3yearlings/hour (average size=9.8 inches). Northern pike abundance in 1994 (2.1 fish/gillnet) was below the normal range (3.0 - 7.9fish/gillnet) for similar lakes, but the same as the historical average. The 1994 averagesize (3.1 lbs from gillnets) was similar to the historical average (3.0 lbs). The largestfish captured was 31.7 inches. Growth rates appear average for ages I-II, but above averagefor ages III-IV. The 1991 year class appears moderate. There were no fish sampled older thanfive years. Historically, Koronis has been a popular angling and darkhouse spearing lake fornorthern pike, especially for trophy size fish (>15 lbs). Yellow perch abundance in 1994 (74.3 fish/gillnet) was above the normal range (7.1 -33.9 fish/gillnet) for similar lakes, but comparable to the historical average (71.9fish/gillnet). The 1994 average size (6.4 inches) was slightly below the historical average(7.1 inches). The largest fish caught was 10.6 inches. Growth rates appear moderate to aboveaverage. There appears to be a strong 1992 year class present. Smallmouth bass abundance (0.8 fish/gillnet) was within the normal range (0.2 - 0.9fish/gillnet) for similar lakes and comparable to the historical average (0.5 fish/gillnet).The 1994 average size (12.8 inches from gillnets and trapnets combined) was above thehistorical average (10.2 inches). The largest fish caught was 15.4 inches. Growth ratesappear average. Local reports indicate excellent smallmouth angling success the past severalyears, especially for larger fish (> 3 lbs.). Channel catfish abundance in 1994 (0.3 fish/gillnet) was above the historical average(0.1 fish/gillnet). The 1994 average size (8.2 lbs) was above the historical average (7.0lbs). There have been no stockings of channel catfish into Koronis, however these fishprobably entered Koronis from the Crow River or Rice Lake. Black crappie abundance in 1994 (0.4 fish/trapnet) was slightly below the normal range(0.3 - 1.7 fish/trapnet) for similar lakes and below the historical average (0.5fish/trapnet). The 1994 average size (0.5 lbs from trapnets) appears similar to thehistorical average (0.4 lbs). Growth rates appear average. All fish captured were from the1991 year class. Bluegill abundance in 1994 (0.1 fish/trapnet) was below the normal range (3.7 - 42.9fish/trapnet) for similar lakes and was the lowest recorded value (historical average= 7.2fish/trapnet). The 1994 average size (5.8 inches from gillnets and trapnets combined) wassimilar to the historical average (5.7 inches). The highest recorded abundance value inrecent years occurred in September of 1989 (6.6 fish/trapnet, average size=0.17 lbs fromtrapnets). Local reports indicated good angling success for larger bluegill in the AssemblyGrounds Bay area (north side), west bay, and Highway 55 access bay during the latesummer/early fall of 1989. About 5,391 stunted bluegill (899 lbs at 6 fish/lb) were stockednear the Highway 55 access (Crow River inlet), north shore access, Tri-County Regional Park,and the west access in June of 1989. There was also some reports (reliable source) of illegalstocking of bluegill taking place during the summer of 1989 (about the same total poundsstocked, but smaller size). It is difficult to assess what contribution if any these stocked(legal or illegal) fish made to the 1989 fall angling success due to the lack of anypreliminary investigation (June trapnetting) prior to stocking, lack of any discernable marksmade (fin clipping) between stocked and endemic bluegill, or follow up evaluation (mini-creel) to determine actual sizes harvested. Factors that would lend credence to little or nocontribution to bluegill angling success include the small number stocked, the high growthobtained in such a short time period (2-3 months), and the lake size (3,014 acres) in whichfish could disperse. However, evidence in favor of significant contributions of stockedbluegill include low abundance of bluegill present the previous year (0.6 fish/trapnet),abundant numbers caught in the 1989 September survey (6.6 fish/trapnet), and the productivityof the lake to potentially allow fast growth rates. Long term limiting factors for bluegillnumbers include the lack of quality habitat (hardstem bulrush stands, largeleaf pondweeds,etc.) and deteriorating water quality (clarity) due to eutrophication. Carp abundance in 1994 (3.0 fish/gillnet) was above the normal range (0.1 - 0.5 ) forsimilar lakes and above the historical average (0.7 fish/gillnet). The 1994 average size (5.0lbs from gillnets) was similar to the historical average (5.4 lbs). Black bullhead abundance in 1994 (1.2 fish/gillnet) was within the normal range (0.5 -4.1 fish/gillnet) for similar lakes, but below the historical average (25.8 fish/gillnet).The 1994 black bullhead average size (9.3 inches from gillnets and trapnets combined) wassimilar to the historical average (9.2 inches). Yellow bullhead abundance in 1994 (0.8fish/trapnet) was below the normal range (0.9 - 4.8 fish/trapnet) for similar lakes and belowthe historical average (4.8 fish/trapnet). The 1994 yellow bullhead average size (10.4 inchesfrom gillnets and trapnets combined) was similar to the historical average (10.5 inches). Management priorities for Koronis include maintaining current walleye numbers throughfingerling stocking as needed (after two successive years of poor natural reproduction),maintaining northern pike numbers through the operation of the two northern pike spawningareas, increasing habitat for bluegill and black crappie (bulrush transplanting), andencouraging local landowners (farmers, residential people) in the watershed to practice bestland management practices that reduce nutrient inputs into the Crow River and Koronis. Bestland management practices include private wetland restoration, upgrading failed septicsystems, planting buffer strips adjacent to shorelines or ditches, using conservation tillagetechniques (no till, ridge till, mulch till, etc.), proper feedlot management, properfertilizer application, and using no/low phosphorous fertilizers when possible. In thefuture, experimental regulations may be necessary to maintain trophy northern pike fishingopportunities in Koronis. In recent years local anglers have more readily adopted a catch andrelease ethic, but it needs to be more prevalent due to ever increasing fishing pressuredemands on area lakes.

Vertical gillnets were set at three deep water (50-130 feet deep) sites which included the north bay (Assembly Grounds), south side (deepest part) and south side of Third Island during mid-August. Vertical gill nets consisted of seven 197 feet deep panels of monofilament webbing (bar-measure mesh size x panel width): 3/8" x 3', 1/2" x 3', 3/4"mm x 4.9', 1" x 4.9', 1 1/4" x 10', 1 1/2" x 10', 1 3/4" x 10'). The 3/8" and 1/2" panels are sewn together vertically into one net, as are the 3/4"and 1" panels. The 1 1/4", 1 1/2", and 1 3/4" panels are used individually for a total of five separate vertical nets. Each net is ganged together by a 12 foot connecting rope for a total of five vertical gill nets with 7 different mesh panels. Vertical gillnets are marked at 3.3 feet intervals and depth at capture is recorded for each fish. Nets are rolled up on custom made axles. Vertical gillnets are set as a gang, connected to each other, and anchored at the gang ends. Set and lift from downwind to prevent boat from floating over the gang. The gang is ordered from smallest to largest mesh (this will be consistent with standard gillnets and allow waypoints for each end). An oxygen-temperature profile was taken each day at each site. All fish species were counted. Tullibee were measured, weighed, age structures taken, depth of capture recorded and fish retained for later genetic analysis. In addition a hydro acoustic survey was done shortly after the vertical gillnetting to determine tullibee relative abundance throughout the preferred zone based on tullibee depth of capture in vertical gillnets. There were 62 tullibee (20.67 fish/gang) captured in 15 vertical gillnets (3 gangs). Tullibee captured with this gear (20.7 per gang) averaged 8.1 inches and ranged from 3.1 to 17.5 inches. Approximately 45% of the tullibee captured were likely young of year fish, 34% were probably age 2+ (2012 year class) and 21% were probably age 6+ to 8+ (2006-2009 year classes) based on historical growth data. The average depth at capture was 19.4 feet. The thermocline in Lake Koronis was set up at 29.5 feet over the deepest area of the lake (127.6 feet). The temperature when dissolved oxygen dropped to 3.0 ppm was 67 F. Tullibee were sampled in waters from 3.3-32.8 feet deep. These waters ranged in temperatures from 59-75 F and dissolved oxygen concentrations of 0.12-9.09 ppm.

There were low numbers of tullibee (6.00 fish/gillnet) captured in the Koronis 2014 fall gillnet special assessment. Only two gillnet stations (SGN3 & SGN4) were sampled in 2014 due to the early onset of ice (November 21, 2014). The 2014 fall tullibee average size was large (2.00 pounds and 15.95 inches) for Koronis. The 2012 fall tullibee catch rate was low (5.3 fish/gillnet, 14.9 inches average length). The 2010 fall tullibee catch rate was moderate (23.8 fish/gillnet, 15.3 inches average length). The fall tullibee historical average catch rate and average length are 30.1 fish/gillnet and 15.20 inches for Koronis. Approximately 92% of the tullibee captured in 2014 fall were ripe males. The 2014 fall tullibee condition factor (1.301) was above the 75th quartile (1.293) for Koronis. Tullibee growth rates were between the Koronis 25th and 50th quartiles for ages 1-4, at the 50th quartiles for ages 5-6, and above the 75th quartile for age 7. The 2007 and 2009 year classes each comprised 33% of the 2014 fall tullibee catch in Koronis. The 2006 year class comprised 17% of the 2014 fall catch. The 2012 and 2010 year classes each comprised 8% of the total 2014 fall catch. There were no tullibee from 2009-2011 year classes in the 2012 fall catch. The lack of adult tullibee on the spawning grounds from early November to early December of recent years as sampled by the DNR is not a good indication for the long term sustainability of the tullibee population in Lake Koronis. Hopefully, cool summers will occur during the next several years, which may result in a good hatch and survival of tullibee in Lake Koronis if adequate brood stock numbers are still present.

Green Lake was not sampled in 2014 due to early ice onset (November 20, 2014). Fall tullibee catch rate was low (8.33 fish/gillnet, 13.61 inches average length) in Green Lake during the 2012 fall.

Improving and maintaining good water quality in Koronis is the key for tullibee numbers to survive and flourish. Public fall tullibee gillnetting seasons will not be reinstated in the near future on Koronis due to low tullibee numbers and high incidental catches of other gamefish. Current fish management activities on Koronis include monitoring the fish population on a periodic basis, assisting aquatic plant management and enforcement personnel with invasive species monitoring and education, protecting aquatic vegetation through the permit process, participating in local watershed initiatives, and stocking various fish species as warranted. The Lake Koronis fishery will be sampled in the 2017 summer for all fish species.

A fall night electrofishing survey of young of year "YOY" (fingerling sized) Walleye on Lake Koronis was conducted during September 29, 2016. The survey was done with a boat set up with electrofishing equipment to evaluate fry stocking success in 2016. The electrofishing equipment puts electricity into the water and fish are attracted to the positive charge in the front of the boat. We then net the fish and take lengths and weights to determine what condition the fish are in (etc.). Koronis is a large (2,968 acres), deep (132 feet maximum), and productive lake located primarily in Stearns County. An invasive algal species, starry stonewort, was found primarily in the east and outlet bays of Koronis in 2015 and near the south access of Rice Lake in 2016.

Rice Lake is upstream and connects to Lake Koronis via the North Fork of the Crow River. Walleye from both Rice and Koronis spawn in the North Fork of the Crow River upstream of Rice Lake. Walleye also spawn adjacent to the east shores of the three islands in Koronis and the east point of Rice. Both Rice and Koronis are Walleye egg take sites for Spicer strain Walleye needs and statewide Walleye propagation program. Historic spawning sites for Walleye in both Koronis and Rice have been degraded in recent years with increased sedimentation, algal and periphyton growth.

Walleye natural reproduction in Koronis was generally frequent and adequate to sustain Walleye numbers based on previous fall and summer surveys from 1993-2002. Walleye natural reproduction or fry stocking successes were poor from 2003-2006 and 2008-2010 in Koronis. Walleye fry (0.5-2.0 million/year) were stocked during 1996 and 2001-2016 as a 10% return of Walleye eggs taken for the DNR statewide Walleye hatching program. Walleye fry stocked into Koronis have been primarily from the Spicer strain (Koronis, Rice, Diamond, Elizabeth or Green) since 2001. Stocked Walleye fry were marked with oxytetracycline "OTC" in 2001, 2007, 2009 and 2011-16 in both Rice and Koronis. Approximately 1.9 million OTC marked Walleye fry were stocked in Koronis during the 2013 spring. About 900,000 fry were stocked each year in 2014 and 2015. Approximately 715,000 fry were stocked in 2016. Walleye fingerlings and yearlings from the Pike River strain were recently stocked in 2006 (2,355 pounds, 45,685 fish) and 2010 (867 pounds, 4,887 fish).

Low YOY Walleye numbers were captured in 2016 (14.2 YOY/hour, 6.5 inches). OTC marked fish accounted for 40% of the 2016 Fall YOY Walleye catch. Yearling and two year old Walleye numbers were abundant (17.5 fish/hour) in 2016. The YOY Walleye historical average catch rate is 43.7 YOY/hour for Koronis. Walleye natural reproduction and fry/fingerling survival was poor in many area lakes and rearing ponds during 2016. Nearby and connected Rice Lake had moderate YOY Walleye numbers (56.0 YOY/hour) due to fry stocking and natural reproduction in 2016. An early ice out in mid-March resulted in earlier than normal Walleye spawning activity which is often less advantageous for fry survival due poor or erratic weather and lake conditions during early springs.

Low YOY Walleye numbers (3.6 YOY/hour, 6.0 inches) were captured in 2015. There were no OTC marked YOY Walleye captured in the 2015 fall electrofishing survey. Yearling Walleye numbers were abundant (22.8 fish/hour, 9.5 inches) in 2015. Abundant YOY Walleye numbers (208.1 YOY/hour, 6.4 inches) were captured in 2014. OTC marked fish accounted for 82% of the 2014 Walleye fingerlings captured in the fall electrofishing survey. Abundant numbers of YOY Walleye (71.3 YOY/hour, 5.8 inches) were captured in 2013 fall electrofishing survey. Approximately 45% of the 2013 Walleye year class captured was OTC marked (fry stocked) in the 2013 fall electrofishing survey. Moderate YOY Walleye numbers (32.8 YOY/hour, 7.0 inches) were captured in the 2012 fall electrofishing survey. Approximately 92% of the 2012 Walleye year class captured was OTC marked (fry stocked) in the 2012 fall electrofishing survey. Abundant numbers of YOY Walleye (205.5 YOY/hour, 6.5 inches) were captured in the 2011 fall electrofishing survey. Approximately 80% (164.4 YOY/hour) were OTC marked fish in the 2011 fall electrofishing survey. The 2011 OTC marked year class accounted for 69% of the 2014 summer gillnet survey catch (19.8 fish/gillnet). Local anglers reported excellent Walleye fishing (16-18 inches) success in Koronis during 2014 and 2015.

The Koronis fishery will be surveyed again in the 2017 summer for all fish species. Fall night electrofishing surveys will be conducted each year to document Walleye natural reproduction and fry stocking success.

A targeted survey of Tullibee "Cisco" in Lake Koronis was conducted during mid-late November of 2019 using lake survey gillnets. A targeted survey is generally used for sampling a specific kind of fish or time of year (i.e. spawning season, fall season, etc.) unlike a standard survey which samples a wider range of fish species during the summer months using standard methodology (i.e. standard time of year, set sampling stations, taking water clarity readings and oxygen/temperature profiles, etc.) and gears (i.e. lake survey gillnets, trapnets, and spring electrofishing for Largemouth Bass).

Koronis is a large (2,968 acres), productive and deep (132 feet maximum) lake located in Stearns County. Tullibee were believed to be initially introduced into Koronis during the 1880's. Green Lake is the only other Spicer Area lake with a self-sustaining Tullibee population. Tullibee spawn in 3-6 feet of water over bottom substrates consisting of large rock during late November to early December when the water temperature reaches 41 degrees Fahrenheit "F" or less. Spawning substrates in both Koronis and Green during recent years have been covered by periphyton/filamentous algae except in shallow (<1 foot) windswept shoal areas. Climate changes may be negatively affecting Tullibee natural reproduction/recruitment success in these lakes due to degrading spawning habitat and increasing numbers of warm water fish species (i.e. Rock Bass, Pumpkinseed, Smallmouth Bass, Largemouth Bass, etc.) which prey upon Tullibee eggs, fry or fingerlings.

Adult Tullibee are susceptible to summerkill in Koronis if oxygen levels drop (<2 ppm) in the cooler deeper areas (<74 F) of the lake for an extended time (1-3 weeks) during late July to early August. Young Tullibee can tolerate warmer temperatures than adult Tullibee. Minor summerkills of Tullibee occurred on Koronis in 2006 and 2010. A major summerkill of Tullibee occurred on Koronis during 2011, but only a minor kill occurred on Green Lake during the 2011 summer. Drought conditions and extremely high air temperatures were the norm for the Spicer Area during July and early August of 2012. There were no apparent summerkills in Green or Koronis during 2012, but adult numbers were so low that summerkill events may not have been recognizable, especially due to the large numbers of pelicans living on Lake Koronis' islands. There have been no documented summerkills on Koronis since 2012. A narrow band of adequate water temperatures (<74 F) and dissolved oxygen levels (5 ppm) was present at depths of 20-21 feet in Koronis during July 22, 2019. Green has been the only lake in the Spicer Area open to the public for fall gillnetting of Tullibee during late November or early December each year since the late 1980's. Koronis was closed to public gillnetting during the late 1980's due to low Tullibee populations and high incidence of Northern Pike mortality during prior open seasons. Green Lake has been closed for Tullibee gillnetting since 2012 due to the low numbers sampled in recent years. Tullibee are an important forage fish for trophy Northern Pike in Koronis and Green.

Tullibee are less susceptible to capture in summer gillnets than late fall gillnets, Tullibee numbers were moderate (1.80 fish/gillnet, 14.17 inches) in the 2019 summer standard survey. Tullibee numbers were not present in the 2017 summer standard survey catch. The Tullibee historical summer average catch rate is 1.12 fish/gillnet for Koronis. The Tullibee summer historical average length is 12.15 inches from gillnets. The 2012 year class comprised 38% of the 2019 summer Tullibee catch.

Tullibee abundance was moderate (27.50 fish/gillnet, 15.74 inches) in the 2019 fall gillnet targeted survey. Tullibee abundance was low (10.33 fish/gillnet, 14.39 inches) in the 2017 fall gillnet targeted survey. Tullibee abundance was moderate in the 2010 (23.83 fish/gillnet, 15.28 inches) and 2015 (19.67 fish/gillnet, 14.17 inches) fall gillnet targeted surveys, but low in 2012 (5.33 fish/gillnet) and 2014 (6.00 fish/gillnet). The Tullibee fall historical average catch rate and average length are 28.57 fish/gillnet and 15.12 inches for Koronis. The Tullibee fall catch rate in nearby Green Lake was low in 2019 (1.75 fish/gillnet, 13.94 inches), 2017 (0.50 fish/gillnet, 11.25 inches) and 2015 (10.33 fish/gillnet, 13.66 inches average length). Tullibee growth rates were slow for ages 1-6, but moderate for ages 7-8. The 2013 and 2012 year classes each comprised about 35% of the 2019 Tullibee fall catch. Tullibee year classes prior to 2014 comprised 95% of the total 2019 fall catch. Hopefully, consecutive cool summers will continue to occur periodically, which may result in a good hatch, recruitment and survival of Tullibee to maintain a long term population in Lake Koronis.

Improving and maintaining good water quality in Koronis is the key for Tullibee numbers to survive and flourish. Public fall Tullibee gillnetting seasons will not be reinstated in the near future on Koronis due to low Tullibee numbers and high incidental catches of other gamefish. Current fish management activities on Koronis include monitoring the fish population on a periodic basis, assisting aquatic plant management and enforcement personnel with invasive species monitoring and education, protecting aquatic vegetation through the permit process, participating in local watershed initiatives, and stocking various fish species as warranted. The Lake Koronis fishery will be sampled in the 2022 summer for all fish species. Tullibee will be sampled by November gillnetting in 2022 for both Koronis and Green Lake.

A targeted survey of Tullibee (Cisco) in Lake Koronis was conducted during mid-late November of 2023 at four lake survey special gillnet stations. A targeted survey is generally used for sampling a specific kind of fish or time of year (i.e. spawning season, fall season, etc.) unlike a standard survey which samples a wider range of fish species during the summer months using standard methodology (i.e. standard time of year, set sampling stations, taking water clarity readings and oxygen/temperature profiles, etc.) and gears (i.e. lake survey gillnets, trapnets and possibly spring electrofishing for Largemouth Bass).

Koronis is a large (2,968 acres), and deep (132 feet maximum) lake located in Stearns and Meeker Counties. Koronis is currently infested with invasive species such as Curly-leaf Pondweed, Starry Stonewort and Zebra Mussels. A standard survey (summer gillnets and trapnets) of Koronis was last conducted during mid/late July of 2022. A fall electrofishing survey was conducted on October 4, 2023 to evaluate young of year "YOY" (fingerling sized) Walleye abundance in Koronis.

Tullibee were believed to be initially introduced into Koronis and Green Lake during the 1880's. Green is the only other Spicer Area lake with a self-sustaining Tullibee population. Tullibee spawn in 3-6 feet of water over bottom substrates consisting of large rock during late November to early December when the water temperature reaches 41 degrees Fahrenheit "F" or less. Spawning substrates in both Green and Koronis during recent years have been covered by periphyton/filamentous algae except in shallow (<1 foot) windswept shoal areas. Increased phosphorus inputs or availability often result in greater blue-green and filamentous algae blooms. Climate changes (e.g. warmer temperatures, additional growing days, increased storm/runoff activity, etc.) coupled with continued nutrient inputs and Zebra Mussel impacts may be negatively affecting Tullibee natural reproduction and recruitment success in these lakes due to degrading spawning habitat and increasing numbers of warm water fish species (e.g. Rock Bass, Pumpkinseed, Smallmouth Bass, Largemouth Bass, etc.) which prey upon Tullibee eggs, fry or fingerlings.

Adult Tullibee are susceptible to summerkill in Koronis if oxygen levels drop (<2 ppm) in the cooler deeper areas (<74 F) of the lake for an extended time (1-3 weeks) during late July to early August. Young Tullibee can tolerate warmer water temperatures than adult Tullibee. A minor summerkill of adult Tullibee occurred in Koronis during 2010, but none was reported in Green. Low dissolved oxygen (<2 ppm) levels were present at depths where preferred adult Tullibee water temperatures (<74 F) occurred for a short time period on Green in the 2010 late summer. A major summerkill of Tullibee occurred in Koronis during 2011, but only a minor kill occurred in Green during the 2011 summer. Drought conditions and extremely high air temperatures were the norm for the Spicer Area during July and early August of 2012. There were no apparent summerkills in Green or Koronis during 2012, but adult numbers were so low that summerkill events may not have been recognizable, especially due to the large numbers of pelicans living on Lake Koronis' islands. A narrow band (1-3 feet) of marginal water temperatures (<74 F) and dissolved oxygen levels (1-3 ppm) was present in depths of 25-30 feet in Green during late July and early August of 2012. Dissolved oxygen levels and water temperatures in Green were at potential summerkill levels of 2 ppm and 74 F on both July 30th and August 9th of 2012. Summer temperature and oxygen conditions were more conducive for Tullibee survival during 2013-2019 for both Koronis and Green. The month of June had warmer air temperatures (up to 90 F) and drier (< 2 inches of rain) than normal conditions during 2020-2022. July air temperatures were near or below normal during those same years. The 2023 summer was warmer and drier than normal especially for June, but no tullibee summerkills were observed in Green or Koronis. Adequate water temperatures and dissolved oxygen levels were present from 17 feet depth (73 F, 6 ppm) to 20 feet depth (70 F, 4 ppm) for tullibee survival on July 28, 2023.

Zebra Mussels were first observed in Koronis in 2022. It is unknown the extent Zebra Mussels will affect Tullibee and their corresponding forage base. Koronis was open to public gillnetting for Tullibee in the fall prior to the early 1980's but was closed due to low numbers and high incidental catch rate of other species such as Northern Pike and Walleye. Until recently, Green was the only lake in the Spicer Area open to the public for fall gillnetting of Tullibee during late November or early December from the late 1980's to 2011. Green Lake has been closed for Tullibee gillnetting since 2012 due to the low numbers sampled in recent years. Tullibee are an important forage fish for trophy northern pike in both Koronis and Green.

Tullibee eggs were collected using a 300 foot gillnet (2.25-2.5 bar mesh) on November 18, 2022 at Lake Koronis for a doctoral research project. A total of 88 tullibee were captured in the overnight gillnet set. Approximately 2 quarts were stripped from 15 females and fertilized with 30 plus males on Koronis. One third of these eggs were immediately shipped to the University of Ohio-Miami. The remaining eggs were incubated in Muskellunge jars at the New London Hatchery for several weeks at 40 F river water and later shipped to the same research facility. The objective of the study was to evaluate the effects of UV light on cisco egg hatching and fry survival. The hatch rate was moderately successful. Local tullibee propagation (incubation, hatching and rearing to fryling stage) is possible at the New London Hatchery if using a recirculation system and a dry diet regime until fish can be stocked in the spring following ice out.

Tullibee were present (0.20 fish/gillnet, 17.44 inches average length) in the 2022 Koronis summer survey. Moderate numbers of Tullibee were caught in 2019 (1.80 fish/gillnet, 14.17 inches average length). Tullibee were not present in the 2017 summer standard survey. The Tullibee historical average catch rate is 1.08 fish/gillnet for Koronis.

Tullibee numbers were low in 2023 November survey (5.00 fish/gillnet, 16.41 inches). Moderate numbers of Tullibee were captured in Koronis during 2019 (27.50 fish/gillnet, 15.75 inches) and 2015 (19.67 fish fish/gillnet, 14.17 inches), but low numbers in 2017 (10.33 fish/gillnet, 14.41 inches). The highest recorded tullibee catch was 119.83 fish/gillnet on Koronis during 1996. Low tullibee numbers (4.00 fish/gillnet, 10.78 inches) were also caught in Green Lake during 2023. The November Tullibee historical average catch rate and average length are 28.52 fish/gillnet and 15.16 inches for Koronis. Tullibee growth rates were excellent for ages 1-8 in the 2023 November survey gillnet catches. The 2017 and 2015 year classes each comprised 35% of the 2023 November Tullibee survey catch. The inconsistency of Tullibee natural reproduction and inadequate adult Tullibee numbers on the spawning grounds as sampled by the DNR is not a good indication for the long term sustainability of the Tullibee populations in Green and Koronis. Hopefully, consecutive cool summers will continue to occur periodically, which may result in a good hatch, recruitment and survival of Tullibee to maintain a long-term population in Koronis.

Improving and maintaining good water quality in Koronis is the key for Tullibee numbers to survive and flourish. Tullibee propagation is an option for maintaining a viable population. Other sampling methodology such as fall electrofishing and summer vertical gillnetting may better sample Tullibee populations in Green and Koronis. Public fall gillnetting season will probably be postponed until the adult population rebounds to adequate levels. Current fish management activities on Koronis include monitoring the fish population on a periodic basis, assisting aquatic plant management and enforcement personnel with invasive species monitoring and education, protecting aquatic vegetation through the permit process, participating in local watershed initiatives, and stocking various fish species as warranted. The Koronis fishery will be sampled in the 2024 summer for all fish species. Tullibee will be sampled by vertical gillnetting and hydroacoustic methods in June of 2024, and November gillnetting in 2025 for both Green and Koronis.

Koronis is a large (3,014 acres), productive, and deep lake (maximum depth=132 feet)located 2 miles south of Paynesville, MN in Stearns County. A chain of three islands islocated along the northwest portion of the lake. The shoalwater substrates are mostly sand, gravel, rubble, and boulder. Aquatic vegetation density within the lake is variable eachyear. Algae blooms are common during the summer months. The North Fork of the Crow Riverflows into the east side and exits the southeast side of Koronis. Lake Koronis receivesnutrient inputs from various sources within the watershed which include agricultural rowcrops/feedlots, lake residential homes, and the City of Paynesville. The North Fork of theCrow River Watershed District and local citizens are actively involved in improving the waterquality within the watershed. Koronis is highly developed with 491 homes, several parks, 5resorts/campgrounds, and the Assembly Grounds Bible Camp (1992 survey). Koronis is a popularfishing lake for walleye, northern pike, smallmouth bass, and yellow perch. Koronis has anexcellent history of producing trophy size northern pike due to the presence of an excellentforage base (tullibee, yellow perch) in the lake. Two northern pike spawning areas (Spaethand Hendrickson) are operated by the MNDNR Spicer Area Fisheries Office each spring. Walleyefingerlings are stocked only after two poor consecutive year classes as documented by fallelectrofishing surveys. Excellent walleye natural reproduction has been documented in recentyears for Lake Koronis. Walleye numbers in 1997 (22.4 fish/gillnet) were above normal compared to similar lakesand above the lake historical average (9.0 fish/gillnet). The walleye average size from thegillnets was 1.0 lbs. The largest walleye captured in the 1997 survey was 28.7 inches. The1995 year class comprised 46% of the total walleye catch in the 1997 survey. Excellentwalleye natural reproduction was documented by fall electrofishing in 1995 (60.9 young ofyear "YOY"/hour) and 1997 (81.8 YOY/hour). Fishing success for walleye has been excellent thelast two years, however the average size of walleye caught has been small (< 1.0 lbs.). Northern pike numbers in 1997 (3.9 fish/gillnet) were normal compared to similar lakes,but above the historical average (2.0 fish/gillnet). The 1997 northern pike average size fromgillnets was 3.0 lbs. The largest northern pike captured in the survey nets was 31.1 inches.Koronis is a popular winter spearing lake for northern pike. In 1997, the Spaeth NorthernPike Spawning Area produced an estimated 8,690 northern pike fingerlings. Smallmouth bass numbers in 1997 (1.1 fish/gillnet) were normal compared to similarlakes, but slightly above the historical average (0.6 fish/gillnet). The 1997 smallmouth bassaverage size from gillnets was 0.9 lbs. The largest smallmouth bass caught in the 1997 surveywas 17.0 inches. Anglers have experienced excellent fishing in Koronis especially for largesmallmouth bass in recent years. Other notable fish species captured in 1997 include normal numbers of black crappie (1.5fish/trapnet), bluegill (5.1 fish/trapnet), and yellow perch (19.4 fish/gillnet) compared tosimilar lakes.
