The largest bluegill captured in the July 1997 survey was 9.4inches. Bluegill numbers have been low in recent years, thus adult bluegill brood stock werestocked in 1996 (12,017 fish) and 1997 (7,448 fish) to boost numbers and naturalreproduction. Koronis has a diverse and popular fishery. Local residents have experienced excellent angling success for a variety of fish species in recent years. Management priorities forKoronis include operating the Spaeth and Hendrickson Northern Pike Spawning Areas, managingfor a variety of fish species, protecting important habitat (emergent vegetation), stockingvarious species as needed, and encouraging local landowners to implement best managementpractices in the watershed (conservation tillage, wetland restoration, planting bufferstrips, proper manure/feedlot management, using low/no phosphorus fertilizers, updating nonconforming septic systems).

A population assessment of Lake Koronis was conducted in late July of 2014. Koronis is a large (2968 acres), deep (132 feet maximum), and productive lake located primarily in Stearns County. Koronis is a popular fishery for walleye, northern pike, smallmouth bass, black crappie, tullibee and bluegill. Koronis receives moderate recreational use during the summer months. There are five public access sites on Koronis. The lake is highly developed with approximately 498 homes and cabins, and seven resorts/bible camp/campgrounds. In addition, the city of Paynesville is within two miles of the lake. The immediate watershed is composed primarily of agricultural row crops, hardwood areas, and residential development. Nutrient runoff enters Koronis via 45 inlets/tiles (mostly small inlets) from agricultural, city storm sewer, and lake residential sources. The largest inlet is the North Fork of the Crow River, which enters Koronis along the east shore and outlets near the southeast corner. The greatest volume of nutrient loading is delivered to Koronis via the North Fork of the Crow River. Aquatic vegetation densities are variable yearly in the lake. Various submergent species (curly-leaf pondweed, coontail, sago pondweed, narrow-leaf pondweed, chara and wild celery) can often become dense in the east bays, outlet bay and near shore areas of Koronis. Submergent vegetation densities were low to moderate in 2014. Water clarity was fair/poor (3.5 feet) on July 28, 2014 in Koronis. Water clarity (coffee colored) was poor during the 2012 fall and 2012-13 winter months, but improved in 2014-15 winter months. Water levels were high during June and July of 2014 due to rain events, but low by fall. A slow no-wake zone was put in place for lakes in Kandiyohi and Stearns Counties during June thru early July of 2014. High water levels due to rain events resulted in some shoreline erosion in addition to many docks and boat lifts floating away from their moorings.

A minor summerkill of large sized tullibee (cisco) was noted during late July to early August of 2010. A major summerkill of tullibee occurred in Koronis during 2011, but only a minor kill occurred in Green Lake during the 2011 summer. Drought conditions and extremely high air temperatures were the norm for the area during July and early August of 2012. There were no apparent summerkills in Green or Koronis during 2012, but adult numbers were so low that summerkill events may not have been recognizable, especially due to the large numbers of pelicans living on Lake Koronis islands. A narrow band (1-3 feet) of marginal temperatures (<74.5 F) and dissolved oxygen levels (1-3 ppm) was present at depths of 18-25 feet in Koronis during mid-July and early August of 2012. Tullibee summerkill conditions on Koronis were suitable when dissolved oxygen levels were less than 1 ppm at a depth of 20 feet with a water temperature of 75.6 F on July 24, 2012, but no summerkill events were observed in 2012. No summerkills were observed in 2013 or 2014. Partial summerkills of tullibee and white sucker are common in Koronis during hot summers.

Rice Lake is upstream and connects to Lake Koronis via the North Fork of the Crow River. Walleye from both Rice and Koronis spawn in the North Fork of the Crow River upstream of Rice Lake. Walleye also spawn adjacent to the east shores of the three islands in Koronis and the east point of Rice. Both Rice and Koronis are periodic walleye egg take sites for the statewide walleye propagation program. Historic spawning sites for walleye in both Koronis and Rice have been degraded in recent years with increased sedimentation, algal and periphyton growth. Northern pike spawning areas are located along the north (Spaeth) and west (Hendrickson) shores of Koronis.

Best management practices (buffers, storm sewer settling ponds, better wastewater management practices, better shore land practices) have been enacted or encouraged by local governments, North Fork Crow River Watershed District, homeowners, lake associations, and Paynesville Sportsman's Club. Koronis is managed primarily for walleye and northern pike, in addition to secondary species such as bluegill, yellow perch, tullibee, largemouth bass, smallmouth bass, and black crappie.

Black crappie numbers were moderately abundant in 2014 (4.20 fish/gillnet) compared to the historical average of 1.30 fish/gillnet, but below the 2010 gillnet catch (7.50 fish/gillnet). The 2014 black crappie average sizes were small from both gillnets (0.10 pounds and 5.12) and trapnets (0.34 pounds and 6.98 inches). The black crappie historical average length is 7.83 inches from gillnets. Black crappie growth rates were moderate. A large 2013 year class of small (4-6 inches) black crappie was documented in the 2014 survey catch. Black crappie ranging in size from 9-12 inches (2011 and 2009 year classes) currently make up the angler catch based on local reports. Black crappie fishing has been excellent the last few years from shore adjacent to the Highway 55 access during the spring.

Bluegill numbers were abundant in 2014 (18.40 fish/trapnet) compared to the historical average of 9.16 fish/trapnet. The 2014 bluegill average size was small (0.08 pounds and 4.51 inches) from trapnets. The bluegill historical average length is 5.04 inches from trapnets. There were low numbers of moderate sized (6.00 plus inches) bluegill (1.28 fish/trapnet). Bluegill growth rates are generally moderate to excellent for all ages. A large 2012 bluegill year class (<6 inches) was documented in the 2014 survey catch.

Northern pike numbers were abundant in 2014 (5.20 fish/gillnet) compared to the historical average of 2.80 fish/gillnet. The 2014 northern pike average size was moderate (3.96 pounds and 24.97 inches) from gillnets. The northern pike historical average length is 24.27 inches from gillnets. There were abundant numbers moderate sized (21.00 plus inches) northern pike (4.60 fish/gillnet). Northern pike growth rates were moderate. The largest northern pike captured was 33.7 inches from a gillnet in 2014. Approximately 72% of the northern pike captured in survey nets were from 2011 and 2010 year classes. Poor winter water clarity resulted in low observed spearing pressure during 2012-13 and 2013-14 winters, but spearing pressure increased in 2014-2015 due to increased clarity based on annual fish house counts and local reports. Northern pike angling (2012 summer) and spearing (2011-12 winter and 2014-15 winter) was excellent according to local reports for moderate/larger sized fish.

Smallmouth bass numbers were moderately abundant in 2014 (1.00 fish/gillnet) compared to the historical average of 0.87 fish/gillnet. The smallmouth bass average size was small (0.64 pounds and 10.40 inches) from gillnets. The smallmouth bass historical average length is 12.58 inches from gillnets. Smallmouth bass growth rates are moderate to excellent. Koronis has been known as an excellent smallmouth bass fishery for angling large (>15 inches) fish in recent years.

Tullibee "cisco" numbers were low in 2014 summer (0.20 fish/gillnet) compared to the summer historical average catch rate (1.15 fish/gillnet) for Koronis. The 2014 tullibee average length was small (8.74 inches). The tullibee summer historical average length is 11.91 inches from gillnets.

Vertical gillnets were also set for tullibee at three deep water (50-130 feet deep) sites which included the north bay (Assembly Grounds), southeast side (deepest part) and south side of Third Island during mid-August of 2014. Vertical gillnets were marked at 3.3 feet intervals and depth at capture is recorded for each fish. There were 62 tullibee captured in 15 vertical gillnets. Tullibee captured with this gear averaged 8.1 inches and ranged from 3.1 to 17.5 inches. Approximately 45% of the tullibee captured were likely young of year fish, 34% were probably age 2+ (2012 year class) and 21% were probably ages 6+ to 8+ (2006-2009 year classes) based on historical growth data. The tullibee average depth at capture was 19.4 feet during mid-August. Tullibee were sampled in waters from 3.3-32.8 feet deep. These waters ranged in temperatures from 59-75 F and dissolved oxygen concentrations of 0.12-9.09 ppm.

Tullibee abundance was moderate (23.8 fish/gillnet, 15.28 inches average length) in the 2010 fall gillnet special assessment, but low in 2012 (5.33 fish/gillnet) and 2014 (6.00 fish/gillnet). The 2014 fall tullibee average size was large (2.00 pounds and 15.95 inches) for Koronis. The fall tullibee historical average catch rate and average length are 30.1 fish/gillnet and 15.20 inches for Koronis. Fall tullibee catch rate in nearby Green Lake was also low in 2012 (8.33 fish/gillnet, 13.61 inches average length). Tullibee growth rates were within the Koronis normal ranges for ages 1-6. The 2007 and 2009 year classes each comprised 33% of the 2014 fall tullibee catch in Koronis. Hopefully, cool summers will occur during the next several years, which may result in a good hatch and survival of tullibee in Koronis if adequate brood stock numbers are still present. Tullibee are an important forage species for both large northern pike and walleye.

Yellow perch numbers were moderately abundant in 2014 (36.40 fish/gillnet) compared to similar lakes, but below historical average of 57.90 fish/gillnet. The 2014 yellow perch average size was small (0.12 pounds and 6.38 inches) from gillnets. The yellow perch historical average length is 6.96 inches from gillnets.

Walleye numbers were abundant in 2014 (19.80 fish/gillnet) compared to the historical average of 10.48 fish/gillnet. The 2014 walleye average size was moderate (1.27 pounds and 14.67 inches) from gillnets. The walleye historical average length is 13.92 inches from gillnets. There were abundant numbers of moderate sized (15.00 plus inches) walleye (8.00 fish/gillnet) from gillnets in 2014. Walleye growth rates were moderate. The 2011 year class (fry stocked and natural reproduction) comprised 52% of the 2014 walleye gillnet and trapnet catch. Local anglers reported excellent walleye fishing (14-18 inches) in both the 2014 summer and 2014-2015 winter.

Walleye natural reproduction in Koronis was generally both frequent and adequate to sustain walleye numbers based on previous fall and summer surveys from 1993-2002. Young of year "YOY" walleye numbers were low from 2003-2006 and 2008-2010, but abundant since 2011 in Koronis. Abundant numbers of YOY walleye (205.50 YOY/hour, 6.50 inches) were captured in the 2011 fall electrofishing survey. Walleye fry stockings (marked fish) contributed 80% in 2011, 92% in 2012 and 45% in 2013 of the YOY walleye catch in fall electrofishing surveys. Abundant to moderate numbers of YOY walleye captured included 2011 (205.00 YOY/hour), 2012 (32.83 YOY/hour), 2013 (71.25 YOY/hour, and 2014 (208.09 YOY/hour, 6.39 inches average length). The 2011 walleye year class was successful in many area lakes.

Walleye fry (0.5-2.0 million/year) were stocked during 1996 and 2001-2014 as a 10% return of walleye eggs taken for the DNR statewide walleye hatching program. Walleye fingerlings were recently stocked in 2004 (2,409 pounds, 48,180 fish), a combination of ages (2,355 pounds, 45,685 fish) were stocked in 2006, and a combination of yearlings and fingerlings (867 pounds, 4,887 fish) were stocked in 2010 due to poor fry survival from stocking and natural reproduction years.

Rock bass numbers were low in 2014 (0.60 fish/gillnet) compared to the historical average of 1.69 fish/gillnet. The 2014 rock bass average size was small (0.32 pounds and 6.43 inches) from gillnets. The rock bass historical average length is 7.04 inches from gillnets.

Largemouth bass angling in Koronis by fishing clubs has been popular in recent years. Largemouth bass growth rates are excellent in Koronis. Standard survey gears like gillnets and trapnets do not efficiently sample largemouth bass, none the less, fair numbers of largemouth bass (0.40 fish/gillnet) were sampled in 2014.

Other species of interest captured in 2014 included low numbers of black bullhead (0.40 fish/gillnet, 0.00 fish/trapnet), carp (0.00 fish/gillnet, 0.40 fish/trapnet), channel catfish (0.20 fish/gillnet), and yellow bullhead (2.60 fish/trapnet); high numbers of white sucker (7.80 fish/gillnet), bigmouth buffalo (1.00 fish/trapnet), and shorthead redhorse (1.00 fish/gillnet).

Current fish management activities on Koronis include protecting important aquatic vegetation such as bulrush through the permit process, participating in local watershed projects, assisting aquatic plant management and enforcement personnel with invasive species monitoring and education, stocking various species as needed, and stocking walleye fingerlings after two consecutive years of poor natural reproduction as documented by fall night electrofishing surveys. The Koronis fishery will be surveyed again for YOY walleye in the 2015 fall and 2017 for a population assessment.

The greatest nutrient loading volume is delivered to Koronis via the North Fork of the Crow River. Water levels were below normal during the summer due to drought conditions, but improved by late fall in 2007. Black crappie numbers were high in 2007 (7.13 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal range for similar lakes and the Koronis black crappie historical average catch rate (0.71 fish/gillnet). Black crappie growth rates were above the Spicer Area normal ranges for ages 1 and 3-4, and within the normal range for age 2. The 2005 year class comprised 98% of the 2007 black crappie gillnet and trapnet catch in Koronis.

Bluegill numbers were moderate in 2007 (18.20 fish/trapnet) compared to the normal range for similar lakes, but above the Koronis bluegill historical average catch rate (9.07 fish/trapnet). The 2007 bluegill average size was small (0.07 pounds and 4.58 inches) from the trapnets. The bluegill historical average length is 4.90 inches from trapnets. Bluegill growth rates were generally above the Spicer Area normal ranges for ages 1-4. The 2005 year class comprised 83% of the 2007 bluegill gillnet and trapnet catch.

Northern pike numbers were abundant in 2007 (9.88 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal range for similar lakes and above the Koronis northern pike historical average catch rate (2.70 fish/gillnet). The 2007 northern pike average size was moderate (3.26 pounds and 23.52 inches) from gillnets. The northern pike historical average length is 23.27 inches from gillnets. Smallmouth bass numbers were high in 2007 (1.88 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal range for similar lakes and above the smallmouth bass historical average catch rate (0.69 fish/gillnet) for Koronis. The 2007 catch rate of preferred size (14.00 inches) and larger smallmouth bass was high (0.63 fish/gillnet) compared to the Koronis historical average (0.36 fish/gillnet). The 2005 smallmouth bass year class comprised 47% of the 2007 smallmouth bass gillnet and trapnet catch. The largest smallmouth bass captured in the 2007 resurvey was 18.90 inches.

Spring electrofishing surveys were not conducted for largemouth bass or smallmouth bass in 2007 due to workload constraints. Local anglers reported good success catching largemouth and smallmouth bass during the 2007 summer. Largemouth bass abundance in the Koronis 2003 spring electrofishing survey was low (15.27 fish/hour). The 2003 largemouth bass average weight and length were moderate (1.22 pounds and 12.22 inches) from spring electrofishing. The Spicer Area historical average largemouth bass catch rate is 46.6 fish/hour from spring electrofishing. Previous spring electrofishing largemouth bass catch rates for Koronis were 36.67 fish/hour in 1990 (0.55 lbs, 9.2 inches average size) and 26.40 fish/hour in 1991 (0.60 pounds, 10.0 inches average size).

Tullibee "cisco" numbers were moderate to high in 2007 (1.88 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal range for similar lakes and above the tullibee historical average catch rate (1.19 fish/gillnet) for Koronis. The 2007 tullibee average size was small (0.69 pounds and 10.82 inches) from gillnets. The tullibee historical average length is 12.32 inches from gillnets. Tullibee growth rates were below the Spicer Area normal ranges for ages 1-6. The 2005 and 2003 year classes comprised 47% and 33% of the 2007 summer gillnet catch. Tullibee are an important forage species for both large northern pike and walleye.

Yellow perch numbers were low in 2007 (9.88 fish/gillnet) compared to normal range for similar lakes and below the yellow perch historical average catch rate (61.80 fish/gillnet) for Koronis. The 2007 yellow perch average size was moderate (0.24 pounds and 7.93 inches) from gillnets. The yellow perch historical average length is 7.02 inches from gillnets. The 2007 catch rate of quality size (8.00 inches) and larger yellow perch was low to moderate (5.50 fish/gillnet). The shoreline seine haul catch of YOY yellow perch was low to moderate (8.22 fish/haul, 2.35 inches average length) in 2007. Yellow perch growth rates were within the Spicer Area normal ranges for ages 1-2, and above the normal ranges for ages 3-6. The 2004 year class comprised 37% of the 2007 yellow perch gillnet and trapnet catch.

Walleye numbers were high in 2007 (10.25 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal range for similar lakes and above the walleye historical average catch rate (8.96 fish/gillnet) for Koronis. The 2007 walleye average size was moderate (1.30 pounds and 14.58 inches) from gillnets. The walleye historical average length is 13.83 inches from gillnets. The 2007 catch rate of quality size (15.00 inches) and larger walleye (4.50 fish/gillnet) was higher than the historical average (3.09 fish/gillnet) for Koronis. Walleye growth rates were generally below the Spicer Area normal quartiles for ages 1-8. The 2006 and 2004 year classes (stocked and natural reproduction) comprised 28% and 19% of the 2007 walleye gillnet and trapnet catch. The 2005 year class comprised 21% of the 2007 walleye gillnet and trapnet catch.

Walleye natural reproduction in Koronis was generally both frequent and adequate to sustain walleye numbers based on previous fall and summer surveys from 1993-2002. YOY Walleye numbers were low (<11.0 YOY/hour) from 2003-2006 in Koronis. Walleye fingerlings were stocked in 2004 (2,409 pounds, 48,180 fish) and a combination of fingerlings/yearlings/adults (2,355 pounds, 45,685 fish) were stocked in 2006 due to low YOY numbers observed in fall electrofishing surveys. The fall electrofishing YOY walleye historical average catch rate is 29.35 YOY walleye/hour for Koronis.

The 2007 rock bass average size was moderate to small (0.25 pounds and 6.51 inches) from gillnets. The rock bass historical average length is 7.15 inches from gillnets.

The Koronis fishery will be surveyed again for YOY walleye in the 2008 fall.

A standard survey summer of Lake Koronis was conducted in mid-July of 2022. In addition, a targeted fall night electrofishing survey was conducted on Koronis during October 26, 2022, to evaluate young of year "YOY" (fingerling sized) Walleye numbers due to natural reproduction and a fry stocking. A targeted survey is generally used for sampling a specific kind of fish or time of year (i.e. spawning season, fall season, etc.) unlike a standard survey which samples a wider range of fish species during the summer months using standard methodology (i.e. standard time of year, set sampling stations, taking water clarity readings and oxygen/temperature profiles, etc.) and gears (i.e. lake survey gillnets, trapnets and possibly spring electrofishing for Largemouth Bass).

Koronis is a popular fishery for Walleye, Northern Pike, Smallmouth Bass, Largemouth Bass, Black Crappie, Tullibee and Bluegill. Koronis receives high recreational use during the summer months. Water clarity was poor (2.5 feet) on July 18, 2022 in Koronis. An invasive algal species, starry stonewort, was found primarily in the east and outlet bays of Koronis in 2015 and near the south access of Rice Lake in 2016. Current efforts to chemically or mechanically eradicate starry stonewort have been unsuccessful in Koronis. Zebra Mussels were first found in Koronis during the 2022 summer.

Partial summerkills of Tullibee "Cisco" and White Sucker are common in Koronis during hot summers. A minor summerkill of large sized Tullibee was noted during late July - early August of 2010. A major summerkill of Tullibee occurred in Koronis during 2011, but only a minor kill occurred in Green Lake during the 2011 summer. Drought conditions and extremely high air temperatures were the norm for the area during July and early August of 2012. There were no apparent summerkills in Green or Koronis during 2012, but adult numbers were so low that summerkill events may not have been recognizable, especially due to the large numbers of pelicans living on Lake Koronis islands. Although high air temperatures (>90 F.) occurred during several days in June of 2022, an adequate narrow band of water temperatures (<74.5 F) and dissolved oxygen levels (2-3 ppm) was present at depths of 22-25 feet in Koronis during mid-July of 2022 (moderate July air temperatures). No significant summerkills of Tullibee have been observed since 2012 on Koronis.

Rice Lake is upstream and connects to Lake Koronis via the North Fork of the Crow River. In the past, Walleye from both Rice and Koronis have spawned in the North Fork of the Crow River upstream of Rice Lake. A Walleye egg take station was operated just upstream of Rice Lake in the Crow River from the 1970's to 1992. However, this Walleye spawning run now appears to be considerably reduced. This is based on anecdotal observations of lower opening Walleye fishing activity near the Koronis inlet bay/narrows area especially since the 2000's and recent (2018-2019) ice out hoop netting in the river near the old egg take station. Walleye fishing activity often was higher during late ice off years at the Koronis inlet bay area due fish returning from upriver spawning around opening weekend. Walleye also spawn adjacent to the east shores of the three islands in Koronis and the east point of Rice. Historic spawning sites for Walleye in both Koronis and Rice have been degraded in recent years with increased sedimentation, algal and periphyton growth.

Standard surveys are scheduled two out of five years for both Koronis and Rice. Fall electrofishing surveys for YOY Walleye are scheduled every year for both lakes. There are presently good fishing opportunities for Walleye, Northern Pike, Largemouth Bass, Bluegill, Black Crappie and Smallmouth Bass on Koronis.

Black Crappie abundance was high (5.80 fish/gillnet) in 2022. The 2022 Black Crappie trapnet catch was moderate (2.40 fish/trapnet). The Koronis Black Crappie historical average catch rates are 2.52 fish/gillnet and 1.23 fish/trapnet. The 2022 Black Crappie average size was moderate (0.35 pounds and 7.9 inches) from gillnets. The Black Crappie historical average length is 7.9 inches from gillnets. The 2022 catch rates of preferred size (10.0 inches plus) Black Crappie was high (1.80 fish/gillnet). Black Crappie growth rates were moderate in Koronis. The 2020 year class comprised 47% of the 2022 Black Crappie survey catch.

Bluegill abundance was high (36.60 fish/trapnet) in 2022. The historical average catch rate is 12.07 fish/trapnet. Moderate numbers of larger Bluegill (7.00 fish/gillnet, 6.7 inches average) were captured in the 2022 summer gillnets. Current fish management activities on Koronis include protecting the important aquatic vegetation such as bulrush through the permit process, participating in local watershed projects, assisting aquatic plant management and enforcement personnel with invasive species monitoring and education, stocking various species as needed, and stocking Walleye fingerlings after two consecutive years of poor natural reproduction as documented by fall night electrofishing surveys. Koronis is a large (3,014) productive lake located about 2 miles south of Paynesville, MN in Stearns and Meeker Counties. It has a maximum depth of 132 feet. There is a variety of habitat and structure which includes shallow bays, three large islands, river channel, flats, and reefs. Submergent vegetation densities often vary annually, but are generally the greatest in the east, west and outlet bay areas. Emergent vegetation (hardstem bulrush, common cattail, reed canary grass) is restricted to one inlet area, west side of Second Island, and bay areas (east, west, northwest). The North Fork of the Crow River flows into the east side of Koronis with the outlet located on the southeast side. The North Fork of the Crow River Watershed comprises about 198,400 acres. There are also about ten small spring/marsh originated inlets that flow into Koronis. Nutrient (phosphorus, nitrogen) loading from the Crow River Watershed is a continual problem. Algae blooms are common during the summer. The lake is highly developed with about 491 homes/cottages, 5 resorts, several parks, and the Assembly Bible Camp. The lake has been managed primarily for northern pike and walleye. Intensive walleye fingerling stocking occurred about every other year (3,000 - 6,000 lbs per year) during the 1980's. Presently, Koronis is stocked every other year with about 1,200 lbs of walleye fingerlings. There are two northern pike spawning areas (Spaeth, Hendrickson) that are operated on Koronis. Previously, Koronis was open for fall cisco "tullibee" gillnetting, but has been closed since the early 1980's due to low densities resulting from summerkills (1983, 1987, 1988). Koronis is a popular fishing lake for walleye, northern pike, smallmouth bass, and yellow perch. Walleye abundance (11.3 fish/gillnet) in 1993 was above the normal range (3.7 - 10.0 fish/gillnet) for similar lakes and above the historical average (7.6 fish/gillnet). The 1993 average weight (0.9 lbs) was below normal (1.1 - 1.8 lbs) for similar lakes, but the same as the historical average. Growth rates appear average compared to local lakes. Natural reproduction is probably a greater contributor than stocking to the walleye population during most years in Koronis. The walleye young of year catch rate was 6.4 fish/seine haul on August 25, 1993. The 1993 fall electrofishing catch rate for young of year walleye from natural reproduction was 37.8 fish/hour with an average length of 6.0 inches. The yearling catch rate was also 37.8 fish/hour, however, these fish could be from either or both a 1992 stocking and natural reproduction in 1992. Northern pike abundance in 1993 (2.2 fish/gillnet) was below the normal range (3.0 - 8.2 fish/gillnet) for similar lakes, but slightly above the historical average (1.8 fish/gillnet). The highest abundance rating occurred in 1977 (3.0 fish/gillnet). The average weight in 1993 (3.3 lbs) was above the historical average (3.0 lbs). The largest fish caught and released alive from the survey gear was 40.9 inches. Growth rates appear good compared to local lakes. There appeared to be a fair amount of natural reproduction that occurred in 1993 as indicated by the fall electrofishing catch rate of 10.5 young of year per hour. Yellow perch catch rate in 1993 (51.4 fish/gillnet) was above the normal range (8.1 - 50.5 fish/gillnet) for similar lakes, but below the historical average (71.6 fish/gillnet). Yellow perch abundance has ranged from 2.7 to 293.7 fish/gillnet. The average size was 7.7 inches in 1993. The average weight in 1993 (0.3 lbs) was above the normal range for similar lakes (0.1 - 0.2 lbs) and above the historical average (0.2 lbs). Growth rates appear excellent compared to other local lakes. Koronis is one of the premier yellow perch fishing lakes in the area due to the large size and abundance of yellow perch present. Smallmouth bass abundance in 1993 (0.4 fish/gillnet) was within the normal range (0.2 - 0.7 fish/gillnet) for similar lakes and similar to the historical average (0.5 fish/gillnet). The highest abundance rating occurred in 1991 (1.6 fish/gillnet). The average weight in 1993 (1.7 lbs) was above the historical average (1.1 fish/gillnet). The largest smallmouth caught in the survey gear was 18.8 inches. Cisco "tullibee" abundance in the 1993 summer survey (0.6 fish/gillnet) was below the normal range (0.7 - 6.5 fish/gillnet) for similar lakes and below the historical average (1.2 fish/gillnet). However, the cisco abundance in 1993 was the highest recorded value since a 1987 summerkill. The average weight in 1993 (1.3 lbs) was similar to the historical average (1.2 lbs). Black crappie abundance in 1993 (1.3 fish/trapnet) was within the normal range (0.3 - 1.7 fish/trapnet) for similar lakes and above the historical average (0.4 fish/trapnet). The average weight in 1993 was the same as the historical average (0.4 lbs). Growth rates appear slightly below average. Bluegill abundance in 1993 (2.9 fish/trapnet) was below the normal range (3.1 - 47.1 fish/trapnet) for similar lakes and below the historical average (7.8 fish/trapnet). Catch rates for bluegill have generally been between 0.3 - 6.6 fish/trapnet with exception to 1982 (36.3 fish/trapnet) and 1977 (23.3 fish/trapnet). The average size was 4.8 inches in 1993. Only 20% of the bluegill captured were greater than 6 inches. Growth rates appear average compared to other local lakes. Bluegill natural reproduction has been rather poor as indicated by the 1993 young of year catch rate of 0.3 fish/seine haul. Poor bluegill reproduction has been due to several factors such as high turbidity caused by algae blooms, lack of cover (submergent vegetation) for young of year and yearling survival, an abundant yellow perch population preying upon young of year bluegill, and declining spawning cover (hardstem bulrush stands). Black bullhead abundance in 1993 (4.8 fish/gillnet) was within the normal range (0.7 - 7.3 fish/trapnet) for similar lakes, but below the historical average (28.0 fish/gillnet). Black bullhead abundance has been high from 1989 to 1992 ranging from 39.9 - 91.3 fish/gillnet. The 1993 average weight was the same as the historical average (0.5 lbs). About 13,350 lbs of bullhead were removed by commercial fishermen from 1988-1993. Carp abundance in 1993 (4.7 fish/trapnet) was above the historical average (2.2 fish/trapnet). The average size in 1993 (4.8 lbs) was also above the historical average (3.8 lbs). Commercial fishermen and the Paynesville Sportsmen's Club removed about 260,000 lbs of carp from 1988-1993. Koronis is a highly developed lake within a large agricultural dominated watershed. Reducing nutrient inputs into the lake should be the primary management goal for Koronis. A comprehensive plan must be implemented to improve the water quality within the watershed. This plan should include identifying specific sites of high nutrient inputs, educating and encouraging landowners to implement better land use practices, educating area landowners about the various government programs currently available that assist in implementing better land use practices, restoring previously drained upstream wetlands to act as settling basins and filtration systems, and provide better coordination between the various government agencies and the private sector for improving the water quality within the watershed. Specific fisheries management options should include the continued evaluation of walleye natural reproduction, recruitment, and the necessity of stocking. The northern pike spawning areas should continue to be operated to assist in maintaining a viable northern pike fishery. If fishing pressure increases and results in overexploitation of certain species (walleye, northern pike, smallmouth bass, bluegill, etc.) then special regulations may be necessary to limit harvest. Other management activities should also include the expansion of habitat (hardstem bulrush stands) for species such as bluegill, black crappie, and largemouth bass. Continued periodic lake surveys, natural reproduction checks, special sampling (ice out netting, fall cisco gillnetting, spring electrofishing, fall electrofishing), and creel surveys are needed to provide accurate information for forming and implementing lake management objectives.

A population assessment of Lake Koronis was conducted in late July of 2012. Koronis is a large, deep, and productive lake located primarily in Stearns County. Koronis is a popular fishery for walleye, northern pike, smallmouth bass, black crappie, tullibee and bluegill. Koronis receives moderate recreational use during the summer months. There are five public access sites on Koronis. The lake is highly developed with approximately 498 homes and cabins, and seven resorts/bible camp/campgrounds. In addition, the city of Paynesville is within two miles of the lake. The immediate watershed is composed primarily of agricultural row crops, hardwood areas, and residential development. Nutrient runoff enters Koronis via 45 inlets/tiles (mostly small inlets) from agricultural, city storm sewer, and lake residential sources. The largest inlet is the North Fork of the Crow River, which enters Koronis along the east shore and outlets near the southeast corner. The greatest volume of nutrient loading is delivered to Koronis via the North Fork of the Crow River. Nutrient levels (total phosphorus=0.030 ppm, chlorophyll a=24.0 ppb) were moderate in June of 2007 for Koronis. Aquatic vegetation densities are variable yearly in the lake. Curly-leaf pondweed can often become dense in the east end and outlet bay of Koronis. Submergent vegetation densities were low to moderate in 2012. Water clarity was good (6.2 feet) on July 24, 2012 in Koronis. Water clarity (coffee colored) was poor during the 2012 fall and 2012-13 winter months. Water levels were high to normal early in 2012, but low by mid-summer.

A minor summerkill of large sized tullibee (cisco) was noted during late July - early August of 2010. A major summerkill of tullibee occurred in Koronis during 2011, but only a minor kill occurred in Green Lake during the 2011 summer. Drought conditions and extremely high air temperatures were the norm for the area during July and early August of 2012. There were no apparent summerkills in Green or Koronis during 2012, but adult numbers were so low that summerkill events may not have been recognizable, especially due to the large numbers of pelicans living on Lake Koronis islands. A narrow band (1-3 feet) of marginal temperatures (<23.5 C) and dissolved oxygen levels (1-3 ppm) was present at depths of 18-25 feet in Koronis during mid-July and early August of 2012. Tullibee summerkill conditions on Koronis were suitable when dissolved oxygen levels were less than 1 ppm at a depth of 20 feet with a water temperature of 24.2 C on July 24, 2012, but no summerkill events were observed in 2012. Partial summerkills of tullibee and white sucker are common in Koronis during hot summers.

Rice Lake is upstream and connects to Lake Koronis via the North Fork of the Crow River. Walleye from both Rice and Koronis spawn in the North Fork of the Crow River upstream of Rice Lake. Walleye also spawn adjacent to the east shores of the three islands in Koronis and the east point of Rice. Both Rice and Koronis are periodic walleye egg take sites for the statewide walleye propagation program. Historic spawning sites for walleye in both Koronis and Rice have been degraded in recent years with increased sedimentation, algal and periphyton growth. Northern pike spawning areas are located along the north (Spaeth) and west (Hendrickson) shores of Koronis.

Best management practices (buffers, storm sewer settling ponds, better wastewater management practices, better shore land practices) have been enacted or encouraged by local governments, the North Fork Crow River Watershed District, homeowners, lake associations, and Paynesville Sportsman's Club. Koronis is managed primarily for walleye and northern pike, in addition to secondary species such as bluegill, yellow perch, tullibee, bass, and black crappie.

Black crappie numbers were moderately abundant in 2012 (1.60 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal ranges for Koronis and similar lakes, but below the 2010 gillnet catch (7.50 fish/gillnet). The black crappie historical average length is 8.22 inches from gillnets. The 2012 catch rate of preferred size (10.00 inches) and larger black crappie was low (0.60 fish/gillnet). Black crappie fishing has been excellent the last few years from shore adjacent to the Highway 55 access during the spring.

Bluegill numbers were low to moderate in 2012 (5.33 fish/trapnet) compared to the normal ranges for Koronis and similar lakes. The Koronis bluegill historical average catch rate is 8.65 fish/trapnet. The 2012 bluegill average size was small (0.16 pounds and 5.66 inches) from the trapnets. The bluegill historical average length is 5.09 inches from trapnets. The 2012 catch rate of quality size (6.00 inches) and larger bluegill was low (1.60 fish/trapnet).

Northern pike numbers were low in 2012 (1.60 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal ranges for Koronis and similar lakes. The Koronis northern pike historical average catch rate is 2.67 fish/gillnet. The 2012 northern pike average size was large (6.83 pounds and 29.41 inches) from gillnets. The northern pike historical average length is 24.20 inches from gillnets. The 2012 catch rate of preferred size (28.00 inches) and larger northern pike was moderate to high (0.80 fish/gillnet). Northern pike growth rates in Koronis were generally above the Spicer Area normal ranges for ages 1-6. The 2009 year class comprised about 36% of the 2012 northern pike assessment catch. The largest northern pike captured was 40.4 inches in the 2012 assessment. Northern pike angling (2012 summer) and spearing (2011-12 winter) was excellent for moderate/large sized fish, but fair for total numbers. Poor water clarity resulted in minimal spearing pressure during the 2012-13 winter.

Smallmouth bass numbers were abundant in 2012 (2.20 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal ranges for Koronis and similar lakes. The smallmouth bass historical average catch rate is 0.87 fish/gillnet from Koronis. The 2012 smallmouth bass average size was moderate (1.07 pounds and 12.05 inches) from gillnets. The smallmouth bass historical average length is 12.80 inches from gillnets. The 2012 catch rate of preferred size (14.00 inches) and larger smallmouth bass was moderate to high (0.80 fish/gillnet) compared to the historical average (0.51 fish/gillnet). The largest smallmouth bass captured was 19.1 inches in the 2012 assessment. Smallmouth bass growth rates were within the Spicer Area normal ranges for ages 1-3 and above the normal ranges for ages 4-8. The 2010 year class comprised 47% of the 2012 smallmouth gillnet and trapnet catch.

Tullibee "cisco" numbers were not present in the 2012 summer gillnets. The tullibee historical summer average catch rate is 1.20 fish/gillnet for Koronis. The tullibee summer historical average length is 12.30 inches from gillnets.

Tullibee abundance was moderate (23.8 fish/gillnet, 15.28 inches average length) in the 2010 fall gillnet special assessment, but low in 2012 (5.33 fish/gillnet). The 2012 fall tullibee average size was moderate (1.41 pounds and 14.91 inches) for Koronis. The fall tullibee historical average catch rate and average length are 31.6 fish/gillnet and 15.16 inches for Koronis. Fall tullibee catch rate in nearby Green Lake was also low in 2012 (8.33 fish/gillnet, 13.61 inches average length). The 2012 fall tullibee condition factor (1.180) was below the normal range for Koronis. Tullibee growth rates were at or below the Koronis normal ranges for ages 1-7. The 2006 year class comprised 34% of the 2012 fall tullibee catch in Koronis. The 2008 and 2007 year classes each comprised 22% of the total 2012 fall catch. A major summerkill of tullibee occurred in Koronis during 2011. Hopefully, cool summers will occur during the next several years, which may result in a good hatch and survival of tullibee in Koronis if adequate brood stock numbers are still present. Tullibee are an important forage species for both large northern pike and walleye.

Yellow perch numbers were low to moderate in 2012 (18.40 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal ranges for Koronis and similar lakes. Walleye numbers were abundant in 2012 (19.60 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal ranges for Koronis and similar lakes. The walleye historical average catch rate is 9.96 fish/gillnet for Koronis. The 2012 walleye average size was small (0.89 pounds and 12.82 inches) from gillnets. The walleye historical average length is 13.84 inches from gillnets. The 2012 catch rate of quality size (15.00 inches) and larger walleye (6.00 fish/gillnet) was high compared to the historical average (3.77 fish/gillnet) for Koronis. The 2008 year class (fry stocked, natural reproduction) comprised 17% of the 2012 walleye gillnet and trapnet catch.

Walleye natural reproduction in Koronis was generally both frequent and adequate to sustain walleye numbers based on previous fall and summer surveys from 1993-2002. Approximately 80% (164.40 YOY/hour) were OTC marked fish in the 2011 fall electrofishing survey. Koronis is a large (2968 acres), deep (132 feet maximum), and productive lake located primarily in Stearns County. Koronis is a popular fishery for Walleye, Northern Pike, Smallmouth Bass, Black Crappie, Tullibee and Bluegill. Koronis receives moderate recreational use during the summer months. There are five public access sites on Koronis. The lake is highly developed with approximately 498 homes and cabins, and seven resorts/bible camp/campgrounds. In addition, the city of Paynesville is within two miles of the lake. The immediate watershed is composed primarily of agricultural row crops, hardwood areas, and residential development. Nutrient runoff enters Koronis via 45 inlets/tiles (mostly small inlets) from agricultural, city storm sewer, and lake residential sources. The largest inlet is the North Fork of the Crow River, which enters Koronis along the east shore and outlets near the southeast corner. The greatest volume of nutrient loading is delivered to Koronis via the North Fork of the Crow River.

An invasive algal species, starry stonewort, was found primarily in the east and outlet bays of Koronis in 2015 and near the south access of Rice Lake in 2016. Current efforts to chemically eradicate starry stonewort have been unsuccessful in Koronis. Aquatic vegetation densities are variable yearly in the lake. Various submergent species (curly-leaf pondweed, coontail, bladderwort, buttercup, sago pondweed, narrow-leaf pondweed, chara and wild celery) can often become dense in the east bays, outlet bay and near shore areas of Koronis. Submergent vegetation densities were moderate (i.e. sago pondweed, water celery, coontail, clasping-leaf pondweed, curly-leaf pondweed, water moss, bushy pondweed and other pondweeds) in 2017. Muskgrass "chara" (native species of the stonewort family) was found at 94% of 2017 transect stations. Starry Stonewort (invasive species) was found at 28% of the 2017 transect stations. Water clarity was excellent (9.8 feet) on July 17, 2017 in Koronis. The 2017 summer was characterized as a cooler than average with normal water levels. Ice on occurred during December 12, 2017, but warm temperatures resulted in poor ice conditions until after the holidays. Snowfall was lacking during the 2017-18 winter.

Partial summerkills of Tullibee and white sucker are common in Koronis during hot summers. A minor summerkill of large sized Tullibee (Cisco) was noted during late July - early August of 2010. A major summerkill of Tullibee occurred in Koronis during 2011, but only a minor kill occurred in Green Lake during the 2011 summer. Drought conditions and extremely high air temperatures were the norm for the area during July and early August of 2012. There were no apparent summerkills in Green or Koronis during 2012, but adult numbers were so low that summerkill events may not have been recognizable, especially due to the large numbers of pelicans living on Lake Koronis islands. An adequate band of water temperatures (<23.5 C) and dissolved oxygen levels (2-8 ppm) was present at depths of 15-24 feet in Koronis during mid-July of 2017. No summerkills have been observed since 2011 on Koronis.

Rice Lake is upstream and connects to Lake Koronis via the North Fork of the Crow River. Walleye from both Rice and Koronis spawn in the North Fork of the Crow River upstream of Rice Lake. Walleye also spawn adjacent to the east shores of the three islands in Koronis and the east point of Rice. Both Rice and Koronis are periodic Walleye egg take sites for the statewide Walleye propagation program. Historic spawning sites for Walleye in both Koronis and Rice have been degraded in recent years with increased sedimentation, algal and periphyton growth.

Standard surveys are scheduled two out of five years for both Koronis and Rice. Fall electrofishing surveys for YOY Walleye are scheduled every year for both lakes. An Index of Biotic Integrity "IBI" survey was conducted on Lake Koronis from July 25-27, 2016. One measure of a lake's health is the community of fish, plants and aquatic life it sustains. Certain species can't survive without clean water and a healthy habitat while other species are tolerant of degraded conditions. Examples of fish that require clean water are Tullibee, Rock Bass, and Bluegill. Species that are tolerant to degraded habitat are Black Bullhead, Common Carp, and Green Sunfish. The more intolerant fish to degraded habitat you have in the sample, the higher the score will be. An index of biological integrity (IBI) is a score that compares the types and numbers of fish or plants observed in a lake to what is expected for a healthy lake.

Koronis is a large (2,968 acres), deep (132 feet maximum), and productive lake located primarily in Stearns County. An invasive algal species, starry stonewort, was found primarily in the east and outlet bays of Koronis in 2015 and near the south access of Rice Lake in 2016. Seine hauls were conducted at 20 IBI stations with a bag seine of 50 foot width and 1/8 inch bar mesh in depths of 3.5 feet or less. A 15 foot wide and 1/8 inch bar mesh bag seine was used at 2 IBI stations. Dense aquatic vegetation (starry stonewort) or soft sediments prohibited seining at 2 other IBI stations). Near shore electrofishing was conducted at all 24 IBI Stations with a back-pack unit in water depths generally less than 2 feet deep. The 24 IBI Stations were spaced equally apart around the entire shoreline of the lake in a variety of near shore habitats. Each station was approximately 100 feet long. Two back-pack electrofishing runs were conducted with the initial run of 100 feet near the shore-water interface in depths of < 1 foot and the second run of 100 feet long about 10-20 feet from shore in depths up to 2 feet.

Approximately 22 different fish species (13 species from back-pack electrofishing, 20 species from seining) were captured from electrofishing and seining combined. Fish species captured included gamefish (i.e. Northern Pike, Smallmouth Bass and Largemouth Bass), panfish (Bluegill, Black Crappie, Yellow Perch, Rock Bass, Pumpkinseed, Green Sunfish, and Hybrid Sunfish), large non-gamefish (Black Bullhead, Yellow Bullhead, White Sucker and Shorthead Redhorse) and small non-gamefish (Logperch, Brook Silverside, Johnny Darter, Iowa Darter, Spottail Shiner, Common Shiner, Golden Shiner and Bluntnose Minnow). Young of year species captured included Bluntnose Minnow, Bluegill, Brook Silverside, Northern Pike, Largemouth Bass, Smallmouth Bass and Yellow Perch with seine hauls or back-pack electrofishing. Johnny Darter and Iowa Darter were only caught with the back-pack electrofishing gear. The various fish species captured in Koronis is indicative of species present in most Spicer Area lakes connected to riverine habitats.

Koronis is a large (3,014 acres) and productive lake with a maximum depth of 132feet. It is located 2 miles south of Paynesville, MN in Stearns County. Three largeislands are located along the northwest portion of the lake. There are several distinctbays within the lake. Submergent vegetation density is variable during different years. In1999, submergent vegetation stands (muskgrass, pondweed species, wild celery, northernwater milfoil, etc.) were low to moderate in density. Emergent vegetation stands (hardstembulrush, waterlily species, cattail species) were relatively sparse with most occurringadjacent to the Hendrickson Creek inlet, west side of First and Second Islands, northwestcorner near Bug Bee's Resort, and the west shore near the Tim Adams Public Access (AC-3).The shoalwater substrates were mostly sand, gravel, rubble, and boulder. Koronis is highlydeveloped with 408 first tier homes, 3 resorts, 1 bed & breakfast, Tri County RegionalPark, Vans Beach City Park, and the Assembly Grounds Bible Camp. The North Fork of theCrow River flows into Koronis along the east and exits along the southeast corner of thelake. Hendrickson Creek flows into Koronis along the southwest shore of the outlet bay.There are about 15 small spring/wetland/storm sewer originated inlets that flow intoKoronis. The watershed size is approximately 198,400 acres. Most of the excess nutrientrunoff enters Koronis from the North Fork of the Crow River inlet, Hendrickson Creek, andfrom surrounding lake shore property. Nutrient runoff sources include agricultural rowcrops/feedlots, residential lake homes, and the City of Paynesville (storm sewer, sanitarysewer during emergency over flow periods only). Clay bank erosion is a problem on severalsteep banks located along First & Second Islands, north shore, and the east shore. Waterclarity is usually fair to poor during the mid summer months in Koronis (secchi disk=4.75feet on 7/26/99). Total phosphorus nutrient levels were uncharacteristically low inKoronis during early June of 1999 (0.028 ppm). Algae blooms are common during the latesummer in Koronis. Several organizations (The North Fork of the Crow River WatershedDistrict, Paynesville Sportsman's Club, Koronis Lake Association, Rice Lake Association)have been actively involved in improving water quality within the watershed. Koronis ismanaged for walleye and northern pike as primary species with smallmouth bass, bluegill,black crappie, and yellow perch as secondary species. Intensive walleye stocking had beendone in the past. However, good walleye natural reproduction has been documented throughfall electrofishing surveys. Koronis is presently stocked on an as needed basis when twoconsecutive poor year classes have been documented by fall electrofishing. There are twonorthern pike spawning areas "NPSA" (Spaeth and Hendrickson) operated on Koronis forfingerling production. Koronis is a popular fishing lake for walleye, northern pike,yellow perch, and smallmouth bass. Walleye were moderately abundant(8.67 fish/gillnet) in 1999 and comparable to thehistorical average (8.99 fish/gillnet). The 1999 walleye average size was small tomoderate (0.94 lbs., 13.53 inches from the gillnets), but a majority of the walleye in the1999 resurvey were young (51% of total catch from 1997 year class). Walleye growth rateswere average compared to other local lakes. The moderately abundant 1997 walleye yearclass in the 1999 resurvey corresponds to an excellent natural year class documented byfall electrofishing in 1997. Excellent walleye natural reproduction success (young of year"YOY" walleye) was documented by fall electrofishing in 1995 (60.85 YOY/hour) and 1997(81.82 YOY/hour). Moderate to low walleye natural reproduction was documented in 1993(37.85 YOY/hour), 1994 (10.50 YOY/hour), 1996 (27.43 YOY/hour), 1998 (3.00 YOY/hour), and1999 (24.00 YOY/hour). Northern pike numbers were low (1.89 fish/gillnet) in 1999 compared to the normalrange (3.00 - 7.89 fish/gillnet) of similar lakes, but equivalent to the historicalaverage (1.97 fish/gillnet). The 1999 northern pike average size was large (3.28 lbs.,23.75 inches) from the gillnets. The largest northern pike caught in the 1999 survey was42.91 inches (20.55 lbs.). Northern pike growth rates were above average for ages III andolder fish compared to local lakes. Yellow perch numbers were moderate (28.44 fish/gillnet) in 1999 compared to thenormal range (7.06 - 33.87) for similar lakes, but below the historical average (65.01fish/gillnet). The 1999 yellow perch average size was small (5.97 inches) compared to thehistorical average (7.03 inches). Bluegill were abundant (23.40 fish/trapnet) in the July 26, 1999 resurvey compared tothe historical average (8.21 fish/trapnet). The 1999 resurvey bluegill average size wassmall (3.59 inches, trapnets), because of the presence of large numbers of young fish.Adult bluegill were stocked into Koronis in 1998 (6,020 fish), 1997 (7,448 fish), and 1996(12,017 fish) in order to boost adult numbers and natural reproduction success. It appearsthat the bluegill stockings were successful in producing several good bluegill yearclasses as documented by shoreline seining in 1999 (11.0 YOY/hour, 1.31 inches averagelength), 1998 (39.5 YOY/hour, 1.30 inches average length), and 1996 (11.8 YOY/hour, 1.36inches average length). Black crappie were moderately abundant (2.73 fish/trapnet) in 1999 compared to thenormal range (0.25 - 1.74 fish/trapnet) for similar lakes and above the historical average(0.73 fish/trapnet). The 1999 black crappie average size was moderately large (0.42 lbs,trapnets). The 1997 year class comprised 91% of the 1999 total black crappie catch. Blackcrappie natural reproduction success was good to excellent in several local lakes in thearea during 1996-1998. Tullibee (cisco) were moderately abundant (2.78 fish/gillnet) in the 1999 summerresurvey compared to the historical average (1.17 fish/gillnet). However, a substantialsummerkill of tullibee and white sucker occurred in Koronis from July 29, 1999 to earlyAugust. Non gamefish numbers were relatively low (0.67 black bullhead/gillnet, 0.20 commoncarp/gillnet) in Koronis during 1999. The 1999 black bullhead average size was 6.69 inches(gillnets and trapnets combined). The Paynesville Sportsman's Club removed 5,100 lbs. ofcarp in 1999 12,000 lbs. in 1997, 12,100 lbs. in 1995, and 45,000 lbs. in 1993 in theNorth Fork of the Crow River below the Koronis fixed sill outlet dam. Koronis has a diverse and popular fishery. Local residents have experienced good toexcellent walleye, northern pike, smallmouth bass, and black crappie angling success inrecent years. Walleye natural reproduction has been good in Koronis, thus requiring nowalleye fingerling stockings during 1994-95, and 1997. In 1996, walleye fry andfingerlings (133,589 fry, 2,830 fingerlings) were stocked in lieu of 1,209,664 walleyeeggs taken in the 1996 spring due to shortages at traditional statewide walleye egg takesites. It appears that the walleye stocking contribution to population numbers in Koronisis negligible during years of good natural reproduction. However, walleye stocking may bea significant contributor to population numbers during consecutive poor naturalreproductive years. Koronis will be routinely monitored to determine if walleye stockingis necessary. Koronis has an excellent forage base (tullibee, yellow perch) for producingtrophy northern pike. Winter spearers generally have the best success for harvesting largenorthern pike in Koronis. Tullibee populations had increased in recent years, however thetullibee population is presently down (1999 fall tullibee special assessment) due topartial summerkills during hot and calm conditions of the late summer months during 1997and 1999. Adult bluegill numbers and natural reproduction in Koronis have responded due tothe stockings from 1996-1998. The growth rates of small stocked bluegill have beenexcellent in Koronis. Management priorities for Koronis include operating Spaeth andHendrickson Northern Pike Spawning Areas as needed, managing for a variety of fish species(walleye, northern pike, smallmouth bass, bluegill, yellow perch), protecting andenhancing important habitat (emergent vegetation, planting willows in the eroding claybank areas), stocking various species as needed, and encouraging local landowners andresidents to implement best management practices (conservation tillage, planting bufferstrips, proper manure/feedlot management, using low/no phosphorus fertilizers, updatingnon conforming septic systems, wetland restoration).

A standard survey summer of Lake Koronis was conducted in mid-July of 2019. In addition, a targeted fall night electrofishing survey was conducted on Koronis during October 16, 2019 to evaluate young of year "YOY" (fingerling sized) Walleye numbers due to natural reproduction and a fry stocking. A fall targeted gillnet survey was conducted for Tullibee "Cisco" during mid-late November of 2019. A targeted survey is generally used for sampling a specific kind of fish or time of year (i.e. spawning season, fall season, etc.) unlike a standard survey which samples a wider range of fish species during the summer months using standard methodology (i.e. standard time of year, set sampling stations, taking water clarity readings and oxygen/temperature profiles, etc.) and gears (i.e. lake survey gillnets, trapnets and possibly spring electrofishing for Largemouth Bass).

Koronis is a large (2,968 acres), deep (132 feet maximum), and productive lake located primarily in Stearns County. Koronis is a popular fishery for Walleye, Northern Pike, Smallmouth Bass, Largemouth Bass, Black Crappie, Tullibee and Bluegill. Koronis receives moderate recreational use during the summer months. There are five public access sites on Koronis. The lake is highly developed with approximately 545 homes/cabins/parcels which includes one resort, one bible camp and several recreational vehicle campgrounds. In addition, the city of Paynesville is within two miles of the lake. The immediate watershed is composed primarily of agricultural row crops, hardwood areas, and residential development. Nutrient runoff enters Koronis via 45 inlets/tiles (mostly small inlets) from agricultural, city storm sewer, and lake residential sources. The largest inlet is the North Fork of the Crow River, which enters Koronis along the east shore and outlets near the southeast corner. The greatest volume of nutrient loading is delivered to Koronis via the North Fork of the Crow River. Water levels were above normal during 2019. Water clarity was poor (3.2 feet) on July 22, 2019 in Koronis.

An invasive algal species, starry stonewort, was found primarily in the east and outlet bays of Koronis in 2015 and near the south access of Rice Lake in 2016. Current efforts to chemically eradicate starry stonewort have been unsuccessful in Koronis. Aquatic vegetation densities are variable yearly in the lake. Various submergent species (curly-leaf pondweed, coontail, bladderwort, buttercup, sago pondweed, narrow-leaf pondweed, chara and wild celery) can often become dense in the east bays, outlet bay and near shore areas of Koronis. Submergent vegetation densities were moderate (i.e. sago pondweed, water celery, coontail, clasping-leaf pondweed, curly-leaf pondweed, water moss, bushy pondweed and other pondweeds) in 2017 standard vegetation transect stations conducted by DNR Spicer Area Fisheries personnel. Muskgrass "chara" (native species of the stonewort family) was found at 94% of 2017 transect stations. Starry Stonewort (invasive species) was found at 28% of the 2017 transect stations. Starry Stonewort occurrence has increased from 17% to 58% of point intercept stations sampled from 2015-2018 by DNR Division of Ecological Services and Waters personnel.

Partial summerkills of Tullibee and white sucker are common in Koronis during hot summers. A minor summerkill of large sized Tullibee (Cisco) was noted during late July - early August of 2010. A major summerkill of Tullibee occurred in Koronis during 2011, but only a minor kill occurred in Green Lake during the 2011 summer. Drought conditions and extremely high air temperatures were the norm for the area during July and early August of 2012. There were no apparent summerkills in Green or Koronis during 2012, but adult numbers were so low that summerkill events may not have been recognizable, especially due to the large numbers of pelicans living on Lake Koronis islands. A narrow band of adequate water temperatures (<23.5 C) and dissolved oxygen levels (1-5 ppm) was present at depths of 20-21 feet in Koronis during mid-July survey of 2019. No summerkills have been observed since 2012 on Koronis.

Rice Lake is upstream and connects to Lake Koronis via the North Fork of the Crow River. In the past, Walleye from both Rice and Koronis have spawned in the North Fork of the Crow River upstream of Rice Lake. A Walleye egg take station was operated just upstream of Rice Lake in the Crow River from the 1970's to 1992. However, this Walleye spawning run now appears to be considerably reduced. This is based on anecdotal observations of lower opening Walleye fishing activity near the Koronis inlet bay/narrows area especially since the 2000's and recent (2018-2019) ice out hoop netting in the river near the old egg take station. Walleye fishing activity often was higher during late ice off years at the Koronis inlet bay area due fish returning from upriver spawning around opening weekend. Walleye also spawn adjacent to the east shores of the three islands in Koronis and the east point of Rice. Both Rice and Koronis are periodic "Spicer Strain" Walleye egg take sites for the statewide Walleye propagation program. Other Spicer Strain egg take lakes include Diamond and Elizabeth. Historic spawning sites for Walleye in both Koronis and Rice have been degraded in recent years with increased sedimentation, algal and periphyton growth.

Standard surveys are scheduled two out of five years for both Koronis and Rice. Fall electrofishing surveys for YOY Walleye are scheduled every year for both lakes. There are presently good opportunities for Walleye, Northern Pike, Black Crappie and Smallmouth Bass on Koronis.

Black Crappie numbers were abundant in 2019 (13.20 fish/gillnet, 2.40 fish/trapnet). The Koronis Black Crappie historical average catch rates are 2.36 fish/gillnet and 1.17 fish/trapnet. The 2019 Black Crappie average size was small from gillnets (0.29 pounds and 7.68 inches), but moderate from trapnets (0.35 pounds and 8.30 inches). Black Crappie 12.00 inches and larger were present in the 2019 survey nets. A variety of Black Crappie size groups were present in Koronis.

Bluegill numbers were abundant in 2019 (39.80 fish/trapnet). The Koronis Bluegill historical average catch rate is 10.90 fish/trapnet. The 2019 Bluegill average size was small (0.08 pounds and 4.58 inches) from the trapnets. Abundant schools of small Bluegill feeding near the surface are often observed in Koronis. There were relatively few Bluegill over 7.00 inches captured in the 2019 survey nets. Locals reported good fishing success for larger (7.00 inches plus) Bluegill during March of 2020.

Largemouth Bass electrofishing survey was not conducted in 2019. However, Largemouth Bass (post spawn) abundance was moderate (21.00 fish/hour) in the late June 2017 electrofishing survey. The Largemouth Bass average size was small (0.70 pounds and 9.94 inches) from 2017 electrofishing survey. Largemouth Bass growth rates were slightly above average for ages 1-6. The 2015 year class comprised 64% of the 2017 Largemouth Bass electrofishing catch. Koronis has been a popular lake for Largemouth Bass fishing tournament and league events.

Northern Pike numbers were abundant in 2019 (5.80 fish/gillnet). The Koronis Northern Pike historical average catch rate is 3.14 fish/gillnet. The 2019 Northern Pike average size was moderate (3.65 pounds and 25.32 inches) from gillnets. The Northern Pike historical average length is 24.04 inches from gillnets. Growth rates were fair for ages 1-7. Northern Pike possession limit regulations for Koronis in the North-central Zone are as follows: anglers can keep 10 Northern Pike, but not more than two pike longer than 26 inches; and all from 22 to 26 inches must be released. Northern Pike taken by spearing follow the same rules except one pike may be between 22 and 26 inches or two larger than 26 inches.

Smallmouth Bass numbers were moderate in 2019 (1.20 fish/gillnet) compared to the historical average catch rate (1.01 fish/gillnet) from Koronis. The 2019 Smallmouth Bass average size was large (1.59 pounds and 13.62 inches) from gillnets. The Smallmouth Bass historical average length is 12.57 inches from gillnets.

Tullibee numbers were moderate in 2019 standard summer survey (1.80 fish/gillnet) and comparable to the historical summer average catch rate of 1.12 fish/gillnet for Koronis. The 2019 summer survey average length was large (14.17 inches). The Tullibee summer historical average length is 12.15 inches from gillnets. The 2012 year class comprised 38% of the 2019 summer Tullibee catch.

Tullibee numbers were moderate (27.50 fish/gillnet, 15.74 inches) in the 2019 fall gillnet targeted survey. Tullibee abundance was low (10.33 fish/gillnet) in the 2017 fall gillnet target survey. Tullibee abundance was moderate in the 2010 (23.8 fish/gillnet, 15.28 inches) and 2015 (19.7 fish/gillnet, 14.17 inches) fall gillnet targeted surveys, but low in 2012 (5.33 fish/gillnet) and 2014 (6.00 fish/gillnet). The Tullibee fall historical average catch rate and average length are 28.57 fish/gillnet and 15.12 inches for Koronis. The Tullibee fall catch rate in nearby Green Lake was low in 2019 (1.75 fish/gillnet, 13.94 inches), 2017 (0.50 fish/gillnet, 11.25 inches) and 2015 (10.33 fish/gillnet, 13.66 inches average length). Tullibee growth rates were slow for ages 1-6, but moderate for ages 7-8. The 2013 and 2012 year classes each comprised about 35% of the 2019 Tullibee fall catch. Tullibee year classes prior to 2014 comprised 95% of the total 2019 fall catch. The last major summerkill of Tullibee occurred in Koronis during 2011. Hopefully, cool summers will occur during the next several years, which may result in a good hatch and survival of Tullibee in Koronis if adequate brood stock numbers are still present. Tullibee are an important forage species for both large Northern Pike and Walleye.

Yellow Perch numbers were abundant in 2019 (120.40 fish/gillnet). The Yellow Perch historical average catch rate is 59.19 fish/gillnet for Koronis. The 2019 Yellow Perch average size was small (0.10 pounds and 6.02 inches) from gillnets. The Yellow Perch historical average length is 6.79 inches from gillnets. Yellow Perch growth rates were fair. The 2016 year class comprised 75% of the 2019 Yellow Perch survey catch.

Walleye numbers were abundant in 2019 summer survey (17.00 fish/gillnet). The Walleye historical average catch rate is 10.93 fish/gillnet for Koronis. The 2019 Walleye average size was moderate (1.28 pounds and 14.69 inches) from gillnets. The Walleye historical average length is 14.01 inches from gillnets. The 2019 catch rate of quality size (15.00 inches and larger) Walleye was higher (7.60 fish/gillnet) than the historical average (4.49 fish/gillnet) for Koronis. Walleye growth rates were fair. The 2016 and 2017 year classes (fry stocked and natural reproduction) comprised 36% and 19% respectively of the 2019 Walleye gillnet and trapnet catch. Walleye fry were marked with Oxytetracycline "OTC" in 2009 and 2011-2017 to determine the contribution of natural reproduction versus stocking. OTC marked fish (fry stocked) comprised 38%, 25%, 33%, 50%, 100% and 100% respectively of the 2016, 2015, 2014, 2013, 2012 and 2011 year classes in the 2019 summer survey catch.

Walleye fry (0.5-2.0 million/year) were stocked during 1996 and 2001-2019 as a 10% return of Walleye eggs taken for the DNR statewide Walleye hatching program. Walleye fingerlings were recently stocked in 2004 (2,409 pounds, 48,180 fish), a combination of ages (2,355 pounds, 45,685 fish) were stocked in 2006, and a combination of yearlings and fingerlings (867 pounds, 4,887 fish) were stocked in the 2010.

Walleye natural reproduction in Koronis was frequent and often adequate to sustain Walleye numbers based on previous fall and summer surveys and markings. However, natural reproduction contribution has been more variable in recent years due in part to degraded spawning habitat and unfavorable spring conditions. Low YOY Walleye numbers were captured in 2019 (1.85 YOY/hour). Abundant yearling Walleye were captured in 2019 (13.85 fish/hour, 9.76 inches). Fair YOY Walleye numbers were captured in 2018 mid-October fall electrofishing survey (20.57 YOY/hour, 7.20 inches). Abundant YOY Walleye numbers were captured in 2017 (65.60 YOY/hour, 6.03 inches). OTC marked fish accounted for 33% of the YOY Walleye catch in the 2017 fall. Low YOY Walleye numbers were captured in 2016 (14.18 YOY/hour, 6.51 inches). OTC marked fish accounted for 40% of the 2016 Fall YOY Walleye catch. Low YOY Walleye numbers (3.60 YOY/hour, 5.97 inches) were captured in 2015. Abundant numbers of YOY Walleye were captured in 2014 (208.09 YOY/hour, 6.39 inches average length) and 2013 (71.25 YOY/hour, 5.79 inches average length). OTC marked fish accounted for 82% of the 2014 Walleye fingerlings captured in the fall electrofishing survey. Approximately 45% of the 2013 fall electrofishing YOY catch were OTC marked (fry stocked).

Rock Bass numbers were low in 2019 (2.00 fish/gillnet), but comparable to the historical average catch rate of 1.77 fish/gillnet for Koronis. The 2019 Rock Bass average size was small (0.26 pounds and 6.19 inches) from gillnets. The Rock Bass historical average length is 6.95 inches from gillnets.

Other species of interest captured in 2019 included low numbers of Black Bullhead (0.00 fish/gillnet, 0.07 fish/trapnet), Common Carp (0.00 fish/gillnet, 0.87 fish/trapnet), Bigmouth Buffalo (0.07 fish/trapnet) and Channel Catfish (0.00 fish/gillnet); high numbers of Yellow Bullhead (6.20 fish/gillnet), White Sucker (6.80 fish/gillnet) and Shorthead Redhorse (4.40 fish/gillnet). The Koronis historical average catch rates for Black Bullhead are 15.61 fish/gillnet and 2.24 fish/trapnet. The Koronis historical average catch rates for Common Carp are 0.42 fish/gillnet and 1.33 fish/trapnet. The Koronis historical average catch rates for White Sucker and Shorthead Redhorse are 5.38 and 1.28 fish/gillnet respectively.

Current fish management activities on Koronis include protecting the important aquatic vegetation such as bulrush through the permit process, participating in local watershed projects, assisting aquatic plant management and enforcement personnel with invasive species monitoring and education, stocking various species as needed, and stocking Walleye fingerlings after two consecutive years of poor natural reproduction as documented by fall night electrofishing surveys. The Koronis fishery will be surveyed again for YOY Walleye in the 2020 fall and 2022 for a standard survey.

Abundant YOY Walleye numbers were captured in 2017 (65.60 YOY/hour, 6.03 inches). Oxytetracycline "OTC" marked fish accounted for 33% of the YOY Walleye catch in the 2017 fall. Low numbers of yearling Walleye were captured in 2017 (4.80 fish/hour, 9.90 inches). Low YOY Walleye numbers were captured in 2016 (14.18 YOY/hour, 6.51 inches). OTC marked fish accounted for 40% of the 2016 Fall YOY Walleye catch. Yearling and two year old Walleye numbers were abundant (17.45 fish/hour) in 2016. Low YOY Walleye numbers (3.60 YOY/hour, 5.97 inches) were captured in 2015. There were no OTC marked YOY walleye captured in the 2015 fall electrofishing survey. Yearling Walleye numbers were abundant (22.80 fish/hour, 9.45 inches) in 2015. Abundant numbers of YOY Walleye were captured in 2014 (208.09 YOY/hour, 6.39 inches average length) and 2013 (71.25 YOY/hour, 5.79 inches average length). OTC marked fish accounted for 82% of the 2014 Walleye fingerlings captured in the fall electrofishing survey. Approximately 45% of the 2013 fall electrofishing YOY catch were OTC marked (fry stocked). Moderate YOY Walleye numbers (32.83 YOY/hour, 6.97 inches) were captured in the 2012 fall electrofishing survey. Approximately 92% of the 2012 year class fish captured in the 2012 fall electrofishing survey were OTC marked (fry stocked). Abundant numbers of YOY Walleye (205.50 YOY/hour, 6.50 inches) were captured in the 2011 fall electrofishing survey. Approximately 80% (164.40 YOY/hour) were OTC marked fish in the 2011 fall electrofishing survey. The Koronis YOY Walleye historical average catch rate and average length are 44.68 YOY/hour and 6.68 inches.

Walleye abundance in 2022 survey gillnets (18.60 fish/gillnet) was above the historical average catch rate (11.28 fish/gillnet) for Koronis. The 2022 Walleye average weight and length were 1.58 pounds and 15.79 inches respectively from gillnets. The Walleye historical average length is 14.14 inches from gillnets. The 2022 catch rate of quality size (15.00 inches and larger) Walleye (10.60 fish/gillnet) was higher than the historical average (4.92 fish/gillnet) for Koronis. Several year classes (2017, 2020 and 2021) from fry stocked and natural reproduction each comprised 20% respectively of the 2022 Walleye gillnet and trapnet catch.

Current fish management activities on Koronis include protecting the important aquatic vegetation such as bulrush through the permit process, participating in local watershed projects, assisting aquatic plant management and enforcement personnel with invasive species monitoring and education, stocking various species as needed, and stocking Walleye fingerlings after two consecutive years of poor natural reproduction as documented by fall night electrofishing surveys. The Koronis fishery will be surveyed again for YOY Walleye in the 2024 fall and 2024 summer for a standard survey.
